WEBVTT

00:01.542 --> 00:02.918
[TV static drones]

00:03.000 --> 00:06.000
[bright tone]

00:14.500 --> 00:17.209
[unintelligible chatter]

00:17.292 --> 00:19.167
- Grandma.
Grandma.

00:19.250 --> 00:21.709
[chatter continues]

00:25.751 --> 00:27.751
- Hey, Soph.

00:27.834 --> 00:29.751
Sophie.
Over here.

00:29.834 --> 00:31.417
- What?
- Hi.

00:31.500 --> 00:32.626
- Hi.

00:32.709 --> 00:34.083
- [laughs]
- Hi.

00:34.167 --> 00:37.667
- Sophie's favorite is
definitely "Twist and Shout."

00:38.626 --> 00:39.959
- Every horrible day
in history

00:40.042 --> 00:42.083
has a much happier day
before it.

00:42.167 --> 00:43.792
- Wow.

00:43.876 --> 00:45.792
[laughter]

00:45.876 --> 00:47.626
- This was ours.

00:47.709 --> 00:49.751
Halloween, 2006.

00:49.834 --> 00:51.959
- Go on, Soph.
- It's okay.

00:52.042 --> 00:54.459
[people cheer]

00:54.542 --> 00:56.959
[dramatic music]

00:57.042 --> 01:00.000
[unintelligible chatter,
laughter]

01:02.375 --> 01:06.542
- I went to bed that night
the luckiest guy alive.

01:06.626 --> 01:07.709
By the next night,
I was living

01:07.792 --> 01:10.417
the worst nightmare
imaginable.

01:10.500 --> 01:12.042
- Police in Manhattan tonight
are investigating

01:12.125 --> 01:14.542
the mysterious death
of a 40-year-old actress.

01:14.626 --> 01:16.250
Adrienne Shelly
was found dead

01:16.334 --> 01:18.584
in her West Village office
last night.

01:18.667 --> 01:21.334
It was Shelly's husband,
Andy Ostroy, who found her.

01:21.417 --> 01:23.375
- The actress,
found hanging in a bathroom

01:23.459 --> 01:26.709
of her Manhattan office,
likely committed suicide.

01:27.584 --> 01:32.000
Shelly leaves behind
a three-year-old daughter.

01:32.083 --> 01:34.334
- Oh, my God.
Look at you.

01:34.417 --> 01:37.167
You look drunk.
Did you drink?

01:37.250 --> 01:39.500
- There was no way
Adrienne killed herself.

01:39.584 --> 01:41.918
- [gasps]
Daddy!

01:43.083 --> 01:45.834
- Suicide simply
wasn't possible.

01:45.918 --> 01:48.459
She was the happiest
I'd ever seen her.

01:48.542 --> 01:50.709
[Sara Bareilles'
"Soft Place to Land"]

01:50.792 --> 01:52.125
I set out on a journey
to find out

01:52.209 --> 01:54.125
what really happened that day

01:54.209 --> 01:57.125
and to make sure Adrienne
would never be forgotten,

01:57.209 --> 01:58.918
especially for Sophie.

01:59.000 --> 02:03.918
-  Sometimes
I still see her

02:04.000 --> 02:09.250
My mother, the dreamer

02:09.334 --> 02:14.042
She'd say,
"Nothing's impossible

02:14.125 --> 02:18.751
Child"

02:20.042 --> 02:21.709
- Cut!
[laughter]

02:21.792 --> 02:24.000
-  And know
that you need them

02:24.083 --> 02:30.834
When your breaking point's
all that you have

02:30.918 --> 02:34.542
A dream is a soft place

02:34.626 --> 02:36.667
To land

02:40.918 --> 02:44.334
Sugar, butter

02:44.417 --> 02:46.834
Flour

02:51.709 --> 02:54.125
[horns honking]

02:54.209 --> 02:57.209
[unintelligible chatter]

02:59.334 --> 03:02.209
[music from "Waitress" playing
over speakers]

03:12.000 --> 03:14.626
- So this whole area,
when you come here,

03:14.709 --> 03:17.375
it just feels
like "Waitress" headquarters.

03:17.459 --> 03:19.751
I love the success of it
and what it means for her

03:19.834 --> 03:21.918
and her legacy.

03:22.000 --> 03:24.876
But then I'm just
immediately transported to,

03:24.959 --> 03:26.209
she's not here to see it,

03:26.292 --> 03:29.292
she's not here
to experience it.

03:29.375 --> 03:31.167
I'm making a documentary
about Adrienne Shelly.

03:31.250 --> 03:33.083
Do you know who she is?

03:33.167 --> 03:35.459
- Uh, I can see her name
right there.

03:35.542 --> 03:39.292
Uh, it's based upon the mo--
yes, that's all I know.

03:39.375 --> 03:40.667
- If I did that,
do you know who she is?

03:40.751 --> 03:42.292
- No, I don't.
- Do you know who she is?

03:42.375 --> 03:43.417
- I do not.

03:43.500 --> 03:45.959
- No?
- Um...no.

03:46.042 --> 03:47.959
- Many people who come
to see the show don't--

03:48.042 --> 03:49.626
just don't know
who Adrienne is.

03:49.709 --> 03:53.417
How she created this story
that has this life,

03:53.500 --> 03:56.876
this amazing life on Broadway,
12 years later,

03:56.959 --> 03:58.250
and they don't know who she is.

03:58.334 --> 04:01.959
That to me is--is--
is profoundly sad.

04:03.167 --> 04:05.626
- I wrote "Waitress"
when I was

04:05.709 --> 04:07.500
about eight months pregnant
with Sophie.

04:07.584 --> 04:09.167
And I was really scared
about having a baby.

04:09.250 --> 04:11.334
I just couldn't imagine
what my life was gonna be

04:11.417 --> 04:13.375
after I had a baby;
I thought it was gonna change

04:13.459 --> 04:14.876
so drastically
that I wasn't even

04:14.959 --> 04:16.292
gonna recognize myself
anymore.

04:16.375 --> 04:17.626
I was terrified.

04:17.709 --> 04:20.918
The actual fear of how your
life is going to change

04:21.000 --> 04:23.167
is not spoken about,

04:23.250 --> 04:26.167
so I--I wanted to write
a movie about those fears

04:26.250 --> 04:28.500
and, you know,
give those fears a voice.

04:28.584 --> 04:30.375
- I seem to be pregnant.
- Good.

04:30.459 --> 04:31.959
Good for you.
Congratulations.

04:32.042 --> 04:33.584
- Thanks,
but I'm not so happy about it

04:33.667 --> 04:35.167
like everybody else might be.

04:35.250 --> 04:37.292
I'm having the baby,
and that's that.

04:37.959 --> 04:39.542
- But I also knew that,
you know,

04:39.626 --> 04:41.500
when you actually
have the child

04:41.584 --> 04:44.626
that this other kind of love
probably kicks in

04:44.709 --> 04:47.584
that you can't even imagine,
which is true.

04:47.667 --> 04:51.667
It's a complete, utter,
unconditional kind of love,

04:51.751 --> 04:55.209
and it does change your life
in a--in a beautiful way.

04:55.292 --> 04:58.209
And it's--it is a love letter
to my--to my baby.

04:58.292 --> 05:00.792
[soft music]

05:00.876 --> 05:03.500
- The first page or two
was the opening sequence,

05:03.584 --> 05:05.751
making the pies
and bread sequence.

05:05.834 --> 05:08.042
And I was like,
"Yeah, you got me."

05:08.125 --> 05:10.042
I loved it.

05:10.125 --> 05:13.083
- "Earl murders me 'cause I'm
havin' an affair" pie.

05:13.167 --> 05:14.834
You smash blackberries
and raspberries

05:14.918 --> 05:17.292
into a chocolate crust.

05:17.375 --> 05:19.167
"I can't have no affair,
because it's wrong

05:19.250 --> 05:21.834
and I don't want Earl
to kill me" pie.

05:21.918 --> 05:24.959
Vanilla custard with banana.

05:25.042 --> 05:26.542
Hold the banana.

05:26.626 --> 05:30.125
- I loved her sense of humor,
her sensibility.

05:30.209 --> 05:34.542
For me to root
for this adulterous affair

05:34.626 --> 05:38.083
throughout this entire script
is such a feat.

05:38.167 --> 05:39.584
- I'm married.
You're married.

05:39.667 --> 05:41.375
I'm pregnant.
You're my doctor.

05:41.459 --> 05:42.709
- Maybe we could have a coffee
or something--

05:42.792 --> 05:44.083
- I can't have coffee.

05:44.167 --> 05:45.500
It's on the bad food list
you gave me.

05:45.584 --> 05:47.083
What kind of doctor are you?

05:47.167 --> 05:50.167
- That balance is so tricky,
because...

05:50.250 --> 05:51.375
- Sure.
- You shouldn't--

05:51.459 --> 05:52.751
you shouldn't kind of--
you shouldn't want...

05:52.834 --> 05:54.042
- Banging your gynecologist.
- These people to be

05:54.125 --> 05:55.083
doing this--right
I mean, it's like,

05:55.167 --> 05:56.250
there's nothing good
about this,

05:56.334 --> 05:57.709
except it works.

05:57.792 --> 05:59.375
- Mark it.
- Mark.

05:59.459 --> 06:00.918
- I loved the script
immediately.

06:01.000 --> 06:04.083
I mean,
it's so fun and irreverent

06:04.167 --> 06:06.209
and true all at once.

06:06.292 --> 06:08.083
- Dawn, you're beautiful.

06:08.167 --> 06:11.042
Your skin looks
like a normal person's.

06:11.125 --> 06:12.626
- Thank you.

06:12.709 --> 06:14.000
- I thought she was
really smart.

06:14.083 --> 06:16.000
I thought she was
really pretty.

06:16.083 --> 06:18.792
She was super ambitious,
I felt,

06:18.876 --> 06:20.959
super clear
about what she wanted.

06:21.042 --> 06:22.959
- She strikes me as a woman
who was ahead of her time

06:23.042 --> 06:25.959
in terms of the kind of art
she wanted to do

06:26.042 --> 06:28.959
and the kind of subject matter
she wanted to cover.

06:30.375 --> 06:31.792
- She's a real feminist icon
to me.

06:31.876 --> 06:34.542
I really think of her that way,
as being a real maverick.

06:34.626 --> 06:37.375
- I remember her
in her wedding gown

06:37.459 --> 06:39.250
and, like, being in the scene

06:39.334 --> 06:40.751
and then going
behind the monitors

06:40.834 --> 06:42.125
and then going back out
in the scene,

06:42.209 --> 06:43.918
holding up her skirt
when she ran.

06:44.000 --> 06:46.083
I mean, I think
it's challenging anyway

06:46.167 --> 06:48.417
to be in something
that you're directing.

06:48.500 --> 06:54.250
But also being a new mom
is pretty crazy.

06:54.334 --> 06:56.751
- You know, Adrienne
was this small person

06:56.834 --> 06:58.000
walking around the set

06:58.083 --> 07:00.459
but quietly powerful,

07:00.542 --> 07:01.876
because she knew exactly
what she wanted,

07:01.959 --> 07:04.459
this was her project,
and you listened.

07:04.542 --> 07:06.083
- I'm fine, Cal.
We'll be right out!

07:06.167 --> 07:09.292
- I wasn't surprised
when I saw "Waitress"

07:09.375 --> 07:10.334
for the first time.

07:10.417 --> 07:11.834
It just confirmed

07:11.918 --> 07:14.167
what I already knew to be true,

07:14.250 --> 07:17.876
and that was,
she was a great director.

07:17.959 --> 07:20.626
- I would've liked to have
seen where that career went.

07:20.709 --> 07:26.250
I would've liked to have heard
and seen more stories from...

07:26.334 --> 07:28.042
her vision.

07:30.542 --> 07:32.125
[baby fusses]

07:32.209 --> 07:34.459
[baby cries]

07:38.125 --> 07:42.083
-  If you're happy and you
know it, clap your hands

07:42.167 --> 07:45.209
If you're happy and you
know it, clap your hands

07:45.292 --> 07:48.042
- In hindsight,
November 1st started out

07:48.125 --> 07:50.584
in--
in a really fortunate way.

07:50.667 --> 07:52.709
I got to spend a lot of time
with her that morning

07:52.792 --> 07:55.125
in a way that I normally
wouldn't have.

07:58.125 --> 08:00.626
And I was really happy
that day.

08:02.417 --> 08:05.000
So we were together,
uh, in the apartment

08:05.083 --> 08:08.167
till about, um--

08:08.250 --> 08:09.959
till about 9:15.

08:10.042 --> 08:12.959
[somber music]

08:19.417 --> 08:22.125
And I was gonna drop her
at her office

08:22.209 --> 08:25.167
on Abingdon Square.

08:25.250 --> 08:27.459
I remember watching her
get out of the car

08:27.542 --> 08:30.083
and go into the building,

08:30.167 --> 08:33.959
and I just watched her
walk away into the building,

08:34.042 --> 08:35.792
you know, and that was
the last time I ever saw her,

08:35.876 --> 08:37.542
you know.

08:40.000 --> 08:42.083
I went to my office.
I was working all day.

08:42.167 --> 08:44.667
I had clients in
from out of town.

08:44.751 --> 08:47.042
All day long,
it was just radio silence.

08:47.125 --> 08:49.709
I couldn't get ahold of her
through email,

08:49.792 --> 08:52.209
cell phone, landline.

08:52.292 --> 08:54.375
The nanny hadn't heard
from her.

08:54.459 --> 08:56.876
Nobody was in contact with her,

08:56.959 --> 09:00.042
and that was
incredibly atypical.

09:01.292 --> 09:02.792
There's an intuition

09:02.876 --> 09:06.959
that something really awful
has happened.

09:07.042 --> 09:11.000
A friend of mine and I were
going to do an event together,

09:11.083 --> 09:12.792
and I said to him, you know,
"We got to go downtown

09:12.876 --> 09:14.626
"and check on Adrienne,
because I haven't heard

09:14.709 --> 09:15.959
"from her all day, and I--
I just--

09:16.042 --> 09:17.918
there's something
that's just not right."

09:18.000 --> 09:20.417
- You were definitely...

09:20.500 --> 09:22.125
wound a little tight
on the way over--

09:22.209 --> 09:23.959
on the drive over
from the office.

09:24.042 --> 09:26.751
And I was trying
to calm you down,

09:26.834 --> 09:27.876
you know, trying to think
of different scenarios

09:27.959 --> 09:30.209
or reasons why you wouldn't
have heard from her.

09:30.292 --> 09:33.250
And then we pulled in front
of the bus stop,

09:33.334 --> 09:35.083
and I said,
"Just leave the car running.

09:35.167 --> 09:36.417
I'll wait here."

09:36.500 --> 09:39.459
[tense music]

09:41.709 --> 09:44.667
- She wasn't
answering the intercom.

09:44.751 --> 09:47.626
Went up to the fourth floor,
banged on the door,

09:47.709 --> 09:49.834
calling her name--nothing.

09:49.918 --> 09:53.000
And I try the door,
and it just popped open.

09:53.083 --> 09:55.709
And that's
when the real panic set in.

09:55.792 --> 09:57.417
It was just palpable.

09:57.500 --> 10:01.125
It was just weird
how the room was just still,

10:01.209 --> 10:04.209
and CNN was on,
and Wolf Blitzer was talking.

10:04.292 --> 10:07.667
But it was low,
and you could just tell.

10:07.751 --> 10:10.000
It was like there was evil
in that room.

10:10.083 --> 10:12.083
Really, like,
that's what I felt.

10:12.167 --> 10:15.792
I felt that there had been
a monster in that place.

10:17.209 --> 10:21.083
- And my phone rings,
and you said,

10:21.167 --> 10:24.083
"Brian, get up here.
Adrienne's dead."

10:24.167 --> 10:27.125
- I just remember thinking
in that moment, like,

10:27.209 --> 10:29.834
"Is--
is this really happening?

10:29.918 --> 10:31.459
This is not
how it's supposed to"--

10:31.542 --> 10:32.876
like,
I was supposed to go there

10:32.959 --> 10:34.709
and find her,
like, talking outside,

10:34.792 --> 10:37.751
and, "Oh, Andy, I'm so sorry,"
like--

10:37.834 --> 10:40.709
like, I wasn't supposed
to find her dead.

10:46.375 --> 10:50.250
- Someone had said, "Andy is,
um, at the police station.

10:50.334 --> 10:52.500
They think
that she had killed herself."

10:52.584 --> 10:55.042
I just remember in my--
in my mind, thinking...

10:56.751 --> 10:58.375
"Sophie.
There's Sophie.

10:58.459 --> 11:00.167
She would never! Never."

11:00.250 --> 11:01.667
And I remember thinking,
"My mom!

11:01.751 --> 11:03.667
She would never
leave my mother."

11:03.751 --> 11:05.542
- This was the time
of her life!

11:05.626 --> 11:06.667
This was it!

11:06.751 --> 11:10.542
This is what she waited
her whole life to have.

11:10.626 --> 11:12.292
And she's gonna kill herself?

11:13.500 --> 11:16.542
- Friday,
I saw the "New York Post"

11:16.626 --> 11:18.751
and the story
they had written.

11:18.834 --> 11:21.042
So I called up Sixth Precinct,

11:21.125 --> 11:23.209
and I asked to speak
to the detective,

11:23.292 --> 11:25.000
and they told me he had gone
for the weekend.

11:25.083 --> 11:26.250
I said, "That's fine,
just give me someone else

11:26.334 --> 11:27.417
who's working the case."

11:27.500 --> 11:29.959
"There's nobody else
working the case."

11:31.000 --> 11:32.542
And he said, "Sorry, pal,

11:32.626 --> 11:34.375
"I know this is not
what you want to hear,

11:34.459 --> 11:37.042
but as far as we're concerned,
it's a suicide."

11:37.125 --> 11:38.667
It's almost like the grief

11:38.751 --> 11:40.375
and everything
that I had been feeling

11:40.459 --> 11:42.042
just sort of, like, pshoo,

11:42.125 --> 11:44.250
just--
just moved away.

11:44.334 --> 11:45.876
And this other thing took over.

11:45.959 --> 11:49.042
this, like, combat mode
of like,

11:49.125 --> 11:51.000
she's not here to fight
for herself.

11:51.083 --> 11:52.292
I've gotta fight for her.

11:53.125 --> 11:55.667
My wife did not kill herself.

11:55.751 --> 11:58.334
- Andy Ostroy says his wife's
death on Wednesday

11:58.417 --> 12:01.626
is suspicious and not
a simple case of suicide,

12:01.709 --> 12:03.209
despite media headlines
that proclaim

12:03.292 --> 12:06.292
that Adrienne Shelly,
the beautiful blonde actress,

12:06.375 --> 12:08.918
took her own life
inside apartment 47

12:09.000 --> 12:10.876
here in this Greenwich Village
apartment building.

12:10.959 --> 12:13.751
- There are emails,
phone conversations

12:13.834 --> 12:16.375
that took place almost up
until the time of the--

12:16.459 --> 12:17.626
of the tragedy itself.

12:17.709 --> 12:19.500
She was making plans with
our friends for the weekend,

12:19.584 --> 12:21.918
dropping off things
to our daughter's school.

12:22.000 --> 12:26.250
That little girl has
to grow up knowing the truth.

12:27.209 --> 12:29.709
Everything changed
the next morning.

12:29.792 --> 12:32.334
I get a call
from Detective Jimmy Piccione

12:32.417 --> 12:34.042
of Manhattan South Homicide.

12:34.125 --> 12:36.250
"Can you come in
and talk with us?"

12:36.334 --> 12:39.292
He showed me photos
of her apartment,

12:39.375 --> 12:43.209
of her desk, of her purse,
her computer.

12:43.292 --> 12:46.209
And then he showed me
a picture of the knot.

12:46.292 --> 12:49.792
And he asked me if she knew how
to make a--a knot like that.

12:49.876 --> 12:52.751
And I told him, uh, no--

12:52.834 --> 12:54.626
and I got angry in that moment,
'cause I had--

12:54.709 --> 12:56.125
and I said to him--
I flipped it back and said,

12:56.209 --> 12:58.500
"Do you know
how to make a knot like this?"

12:58.584 --> 12:59.792
And he said, "No."

12:59.876 --> 13:02.125
That day, I also called
Dr. Michael Baden,

13:02.209 --> 13:05.334
who's a world-renowned
forensic pathologist,

13:05.417 --> 13:07.542
so he was scheduled
to do an autopsy

13:07.626 --> 13:08.792
the next day, Saturday.

13:08.876 --> 13:13.334
I remember getting the call
from Baden that Saturday

13:13.417 --> 13:16.542
and hearing him say,
"She fought like an animal."

13:16.626 --> 13:19.250
- She had bruises on her body,
bruises on her face,

13:19.334 --> 13:23.042
forehead,
mostly left side of the face,

13:23.125 --> 13:27.167
and, um, inju--
injuries to her hands,

13:27.250 --> 13:30.250
uh, which would
indicate a struggle.

13:30.334 --> 13:32.834
We don't see that in suicides.

13:32.918 --> 13:35.375
- Everything I wanted
so desperately

13:35.459 --> 13:37.209
was being given to me
in that moment.

13:37.292 --> 13:40.083
Like, she didn't kill herself.
Like, here it is.

13:40.167 --> 13:42.459
Here's this--
here's some proof.

13:42.542 --> 13:44.334
And then just immediately,

13:44.417 --> 13:47.834
I'm starting to envision
what did happen.

13:54.626 --> 13:57.626
There she is.
- Where?

13:57.709 --> 14:00.918
Oh.
- Love that quote.

14:01.000 --> 14:04.417
- "Don't be afraid of dying.
Be afraid of never living."

14:04.500 --> 14:05.584
- True dat.

14:05.667 --> 14:08.083
You're almost the same age
as her here.

14:14.125 --> 14:17.918
Oh, Lennon,
your mother loved John Lennon.

14:18.000 --> 14:20.792
What are you feeling as you're
going through this stuff?

14:20.876 --> 14:23.209
- It's interesting.

14:23.292 --> 14:27.042
Just, like, learning more
about, like, who she was.

14:27.125 --> 14:28.876
- Look at that.
What does that say?

14:28.959 --> 14:31.083
Soph.
- What is it?

14:31.167 --> 14:32.542
- "I hate camp.
Take me home."

14:32.626 --> 14:33.500
- Oh--
oh.

14:33.584 --> 14:34.500
- Boy, that sounds familiar,
huh?

14:34.584 --> 14:35.709
- Did she hate camp?

14:35.792 --> 14:37.334
[gasps]
What?

14:37.417 --> 14:40.375
- "Allison is my new,
nice friend.

14:40.459 --> 14:41.792
She hates it here too."

14:41.876 --> 14:43.626
That's literally--
oh, my God.

14:43.709 --> 14:45.125
- I've literally gotten
that letter from you.

14:45.209 --> 14:47.167
- Gotta take that home, Andy.

14:47.876 --> 14:50.125
- Oh, that's a beautiful face,
Mrs. Levine.

14:50.209 --> 14:52.626
Do you have any tips
on how other families could

14:52.709 --> 14:56.459
reach the level of intelligence
that yours has?

14:56.542 --> 14:58.292
- [laughs]
- Is that all you have to say?

14:58.375 --> 14:59.417
Okay.

14:59.500 --> 15:02.876
- The day she was born
was beautiful.

15:02.959 --> 15:06.334
She was so beautiful,
that chubby little face,

15:06.417 --> 15:08.751
those cheeks,
that little mouth.

15:08.834 --> 15:11.834
Beautiful eyes--
she was beautiful.

15:11.918 --> 15:15.751
And she looked exactly
like Shelly, my first husband.

15:15.834 --> 15:18.292
The exact same face,
so of course,

15:18.375 --> 15:19.542
my husband was thrilled.

15:19.626 --> 15:20.667
You know what?

15:20.751 --> 15:22.792
She really knew
what she wanted.

15:22.876 --> 15:24.042
From when she was
five years old,

15:24.125 --> 15:26.125
when she was in kindergarten,
"Guys and Dolls,"

15:26.209 --> 15:27.334
that was the play.

15:27.417 --> 15:28.792
It was so cute.

15:28.876 --> 15:30.125
Every year, they had plays,

15:30.209 --> 15:32.167
and she was always
in everything.

15:32.250 --> 15:34.959
She always, always stood out.

15:35.042 --> 15:37.542
It was always Adrienne, like--
whew!

15:37.626 --> 15:39.959
- My crib was actually in--
in Adrienne's room.

15:40.042 --> 15:41.959
I was actually
one of her dolls.

15:42.042 --> 15:43.334
That's how she treated me.

15:43.417 --> 15:45.375
Adrienne used to like
to dress me up.

15:45.459 --> 15:47.834
My father was still alive
at the point,

15:47.918 --> 15:48.959
and I remember he was like,

15:49.042 --> 15:50.959
"What are you dressing him
in that--in that crap?"

15:51.042 --> 15:53.125
Adrienne just said,
"I don't know, it looks cute."

15:57.042 --> 16:01.709
- Adrienne had a lot of fear
about dying young.

16:01.792 --> 16:02.792
Shelly, whose name she took

16:02.876 --> 16:06.334
when she started working
professionally, um,

16:06.417 --> 16:08.417
when she was 12 years old
and away at sleepaway camp,

16:08.500 --> 16:11.876
he died
of a massive heart attack.

16:14.292 --> 16:17.375
Which left her with feelings
of her own mortality, uh,

16:17.459 --> 16:19.918
of, you know,
"Am I gonna die young?

16:20.000 --> 16:21.918
"If I die young
and I have a child,

16:22.000 --> 16:23.292
what--
what does that do?"

16:25.375 --> 16:29.167
When she was 12, that was
the summer when Shelly died.

16:29.250 --> 16:31.250
- Yes.
It was a horrible time.

16:31.334 --> 16:33.500
And I remember sitting
on the bed with them

16:33.584 --> 16:36.000
and holding the three of them,
and I said,

16:36.083 --> 16:38.459
"We're gonna get through it.
I promise you--

16:38.542 --> 16:41.292
I promise you
we will get through it."

16:41.375 --> 16:42.709
- This is an odd thing
you and I have in common,

16:42.792 --> 16:43.751
I just realized.

16:43.834 --> 16:45.083
- What was that?
What do we--

16:45.167 --> 16:46.918
- Telling little kids that...
- Oh!

16:47.000 --> 16:47.918
- Mommy or Daddy's not
coming home anymore.

16:48.000 --> 16:49.417
- Hello.
Right.

16:49.500 --> 16:50.918
She went into a funk.
- Uh-huh.

16:51.000 --> 16:53.667
- She really did.
She became very quiet.

16:54.500 --> 16:57.584
- "I wonder just how much
of life is spent in mourning.

16:57.667 --> 17:00.542
"It seems I mourn daily
over something or other.

17:00.626 --> 17:02.918
"Even when I am not mourning
over a person,

17:03.000 --> 17:05.417
"I am mourning
over my own inadequacies--

17:05.500 --> 17:07.709
"my feeble height,
my heavy thighs,

17:07.792 --> 17:10.500
my incessant fears, my habits."

17:10.584 --> 17:12.250
- I didn't know her
when her father died.

17:12.334 --> 17:13.459
- Mm-hmm.
- I remember

17:13.542 --> 17:16.042
we were in my house, and I
don't remember exactly how

17:16.125 --> 17:17.542
she started talking about him.

17:17.626 --> 17:19.751
She never talked
about him, really.

17:19.834 --> 17:22.000
And she started crying.
And I hugged her.

17:22.083 --> 17:24.459
And it was kind of just
a moment where I just

17:24.542 --> 17:26.500
held her and hugged her
while she cried.

17:26.584 --> 17:28.125
And then she revealed to me
after that

17:28.209 --> 17:30.459
that was the first time
she cried to anybody...

17:30.542 --> 17:32.834
- Mm.
- About him.

17:32.918 --> 17:35.292
And, um, well,
we were already 16.

17:39.083 --> 17:40.584
- Were there ever times
when you just come in

17:40.667 --> 17:42.584
and you close the door
and you cry?

17:43.417 --> 17:45.167
- No.

17:45.250 --> 17:46.584
I haven't cried in a while.

17:46.667 --> 17:49.250
Like, I don't cry about it.
- Mm-hmm.

17:49.334 --> 17:51.125
- I don't really
show my emotions.

17:51.209 --> 17:52.292
- Mm-hmm.

17:52.375 --> 17:55.209
Do you ever worry that
that's not healthy for you?

17:55.292 --> 17:58.083
- Yeah.
It's not.

17:58.167 --> 17:59.918
- How do you think
it's not healthy?

18:00.000 --> 18:01.834
- 'Cause you need
to let it out.

18:01.918 --> 18:04.709
I haven't had, like, a--
like, a cry...

18:04.792 --> 18:06.792
- Mm-hmm.

18:06.876 --> 18:08.167
- In, like, years.
- Mm-hmm.

18:08.250 --> 18:10.375
- I don't even remember.

18:10.459 --> 18:12.209
- Whee!

18:12.292 --> 18:14.626
Whee!
- Whoo!

18:14.709 --> 18:16.167
- Wanna sing the alphabet song
with me?

18:16.250 --> 18:17.334
- Yes.
- Okay.

18:17.417 --> 18:22.042
both:  A, B, C, D, E, F, G

18:22.125 --> 18:24.876
- I'd gone to a psychiatrist
to...

18:24.959 --> 18:26.500
find out how--
what do I say

18:26.584 --> 18:30.083
to a kid who's not even three?

18:30.834 --> 18:33.751
They can't really handle much,
so it's just very specific,

18:33.834 --> 18:36.584
you know, "Mommy died.

18:36.667 --> 18:38.584
"Her body stopped working.

18:38.667 --> 18:40.834
She's not coming home anymore."

18:41.709 --> 18:43.459
That's it.

18:43.542 --> 18:45.459
And so that's what I told her.

18:45.542 --> 18:48.417
And then I remember
she walked over to the window,

18:48.500 --> 18:52.375
and she just stared out the
window, and I was beside her.

18:52.459 --> 18:53.834
She just...

18:55.417 --> 18:59.709
Turned to me and said,
"Mommy died.

18:59.792 --> 19:02.125
She's not coming back."

19:02.209 --> 19:06.500
Then I said, "Nope,
she's not coming back."

19:06.584 --> 19:09.292
And she just stared
right out the window.

19:11.626 --> 19:13.459
And that was it.

19:21.584 --> 19:24.209
Over the years, Sophie
and I had what I thought

19:24.292 --> 19:27.042
were incredibly deep
conversations about Adrienne.

19:27.125 --> 19:29.792
I felt it was important
in those moments

19:29.876 --> 19:32.209
to capture them forever.

19:32.292 --> 19:35.834
So I copied them down
verbatim.

19:38.167 --> 19:39.417
- I really miss Mommy.

19:39.500 --> 19:40.584
- I know, sweetie.

19:40.667 --> 19:41.918
What made you think
of that just now?

19:42.000 --> 19:43.250
- I just miss being with her.

19:43.334 --> 19:45.375
It makes me cry.

19:45.459 --> 19:47.417
We used to do stuff together,
and I miss her.

19:47.500 --> 19:49.417
- I know.
I wish I could have saved her.

19:49.500 --> 19:51.667
It's so unfair.
- Especially to me,

19:51.751 --> 19:54.375
because everybody else has
a mommy, and I don't.

19:55.792 --> 19:58.042
I wonder what it's like
to have a mom.

19:58.125 --> 20:01.000
[soft music]

20:11.751 --> 20:13.834
- She was probably
one of the most

20:13.918 --> 20:15.500
loyal friends I've ever had.

20:15.584 --> 20:19.209
She was fiercely loyal
and supportive.

20:20.209 --> 20:22.125
- Did Adrienne perform here?
- No.

20:22.209 --> 20:23.626
I don't remember Adrienne here.
- Yes, she did.

20:23.709 --> 20:24.626
- She did?
- She did.

20:24.709 --> 20:25.626
- I thought it was
the other theater.

20:25.709 --> 20:26.751
- No.
She did--they did, um...

20:26.834 --> 20:28.167
- She did here?
- I'm gonna guess

20:28.250 --> 20:29.626
it was "Pippin."

20:40.375 --> 20:42.417
- You got it?
Let's see.

20:42.500 --> 20:44.250
Oh, right.

20:44.334 --> 20:47.459
- Did she call herself
Adrienne Shelly in 1984?

20:47.542 --> 20:49.959
- Anytime she could
use Shelly's name, she did.

20:50.042 --> 20:52.000
- Mm-hmm.

20:52.083 --> 20:54.167
- Andy, do me a favor.
- What?

20:54.250 --> 20:56.918
- Put your hand together
with me here.

20:57.000 --> 20:59.834
Okay.
It's for Sophie too.

20:59.918 --> 21:02.250
Love you, A.
Love you.

21:06.417 --> 21:10.292
[gentle piano music playing]

21:10.375 --> 21:11.959
- She was great on the piano.

21:12.042 --> 21:13.334
She could play anything
by ear.

21:13.417 --> 21:15.626
I don't remember her
taking piano lessons.

21:15.709 --> 21:17.959
She could just get on and play
and sing.

21:18.042 --> 21:19.125
It was quite amazing.

21:19.209 --> 21:20.834
-  And it's good to know

21:20.918 --> 21:26.500
My best friend
has come home again

21:26.584 --> 21:29.292
- We met through
our ninth grade chorus class.

21:29.375 --> 21:32.584
The teacher clearly
recognized Adrienne's voice

21:32.667 --> 21:34.709
and gave her a solo.

21:34.792 --> 21:38.209
And I remember hearing
this voice--

21:38.292 --> 21:42.042
like, she belted it,
and, uh, it was unreal.

21:42.125 --> 21:48.876
-  Come in from the rain

21:49.626 --> 21:52.876
- That was really the first
time where you could tell

21:52.959 --> 21:55.334
that this was something
she was really serious about.

21:58.083 --> 22:00.751
- Um, Adrienne Lauren Levine.

22:00.834 --> 22:03.751
- We kept in touch
all through college,

22:03.834 --> 22:06.876
even though we were, you know,
in separate locations,

22:06.959 --> 22:08.334
and I actually remember,
junior year,

22:08.417 --> 22:11.000
she called me to tell me
she was leaving college.

22:11.083 --> 22:13.876
She was running it by me
before she had told her mom.

22:13.959 --> 22:15.626
- Really?
- Yes.

22:15.709 --> 22:16.918
- What was your an--uh...
- She said--

22:17.000 --> 22:19.083
- Advice?
- She called me up, she says,

22:19.167 --> 22:20.751
"I think I wanna
drop out of college

22:20.834 --> 22:22.250
"and move to New York
and become an actress.

22:22.334 --> 22:24.209
What do you think?"

22:24.292 --> 22:26.250
So I said, "Oh--
well, if that's..."

22:26.334 --> 22:28.083
- Sounds logical.
- "What you want to do."

22:28.167 --> 22:30.918
She's like, "Well, I--
I'm nervous to tell my mom."

22:31.000 --> 22:33.751
- And I said, "Oh,
what are you talking about?

22:33.834 --> 22:35.792
You have one more year."

22:35.876 --> 22:37.876
"Ma, I wanna--
I know what I want.

22:37.959 --> 22:40.083
"It's--
it's such a calling for me.

22:40.167 --> 22:42.542
It's--it's--
it's my calling."

22:44.334 --> 22:46.209
- "Well, I'm doing it.

22:46.292 --> 22:48.083
"I'm leaving school.
It's all done.

22:48.167 --> 22:51.042
"All of a sudden,
I've taken a huge risk.

22:51.125 --> 22:53.375
"I face a new jungle now,
with strange faces,

22:53.459 --> 22:58.250
situations, rejections, and
joys I can't even imagine."

23:01.209 --> 23:04.834
"June 7, 1987.
Happy June.

23:04.918 --> 23:07.459
"Happy month of my 21st year.

23:07.542 --> 23:09.125
"New York has given me much

23:09.209 --> 23:11.292
"in the four months
I've lived here.

23:11.375 --> 23:14.459
"It has virtually ended
the long depression sessions,

23:14.542 --> 23:17.792
"which were once
a signature characteristic.

23:17.876 --> 23:19.751
"It has taught me a lot
about myself

23:19.834 --> 23:23.417
that I wouldn't have learned,
not for a while, without it."

23:23.500 --> 23:26.459
[soaring music]

23:30.542 --> 23:34.959
- She sent her headshot out
to hundreds of people.

23:35.042 --> 23:37.918
One showed up and my office,
and I liked it.

23:38.000 --> 23:40.417
- She got the part right away.

23:40.500 --> 23:43.083
And I said, "Oh, we did right.
We did right."

23:45.417 --> 23:46.500
- It happened quickly.

23:46.584 --> 23:50.292
Like, in no time,
she was now the star

23:50.375 --> 23:55.042
of this indie cult film.

23:55.125 --> 23:57.542
- Adrienne was
the first actress

23:57.626 --> 23:58.834
that I was asked to read with.

23:58.918 --> 24:00.626
Hal had already
given me the role.

24:00.709 --> 24:02.667
- Hi.
- Hello.

24:02.751 --> 24:04.626
- Can I help you find
something?

24:04.709 --> 24:06.626
- This I remember more
than anything.

24:06.709 --> 24:09.083
Her evaluating me.
She doesn't have the role.

24:09.167 --> 24:11.042
Do you work here?
- I happen to be a big fan

24:11.125 --> 24:12.792
of George Washington myself.

24:12.876 --> 24:14.709
- Really?
But she was just kind of

24:14.792 --> 24:16.792
giving me a--
you know, a once-over.

24:16.876 --> 24:18.792
- I can't help thinking
that if he were alive today,

24:18.876 --> 24:20.751
doing the job he did then,

24:20.834 --> 24:22.584
leading that particular
revolution,

24:22.667 --> 24:25.042
he'd be locked up
or worse.

24:25.125 --> 24:26.334
- Yeah,
she was a complete unicorn

24:26.417 --> 24:27.375
as far as I was concerned.

24:27.459 --> 24:28.584
She scared me a little.

24:28.667 --> 24:31.709
Um, she said certain things
to me that totally unnerved me.

24:31.792 --> 24:33.834
- All of them--
Franklin, Payne, Jefferson,

24:33.918 --> 24:35.209
they'd be executed.

24:35.292 --> 24:38.709
- Well, maybe not executed.
- Oh, don't put it past people.

24:38.792 --> 24:41.209
- Not in a bad way,
just made me think.

24:41.292 --> 24:43.375
[mellow guitar music]

24:43.459 --> 24:45.584
- I hardly remember
directing her at all,

24:45.667 --> 24:47.334
because once I cast her,

24:47.417 --> 24:49.667
I just didn't have to worry
about her at all.

24:49.751 --> 24:51.000
She always knew her lines.

24:51.083 --> 24:53.167
She was always funny
in the right way.

24:53.250 --> 24:54.792
She was consistent.

24:54.876 --> 24:56.709
She was perfect for that role.

24:59.000 --> 25:01.834
The Toronto Film Festival
selected it,

25:01.918 --> 25:03.459
and it was a big hit there,

25:03.542 --> 25:05.417
and that's where
everything started.

25:05.500 --> 25:07.918
Miramax bought the rights
to it.

25:08.000 --> 25:10.542
In that company
was Harvey Weinstein.

25:10.626 --> 25:12.250
It's always an argument.

25:12.334 --> 25:14.125
He wanted me to recut the film,

25:14.209 --> 25:19.209
particularly to add some degree
of nudity with Adrienne.

25:19.292 --> 25:23.083
And I was like, "No.
The film as it is, is fine."

25:23.167 --> 25:24.709
- Dad, give me $5.

25:24.792 --> 25:25.709
- Listen to me, young lady,

25:25.792 --> 25:27.375
I've had just about
all I'm gonna take.

25:27.459 --> 25:29.792
- Mom, what's he talkin' about?
Give me $5.

25:29.876 --> 25:32.375
Well, "The Unbelievable Truth"
was my first film.

25:32.459 --> 25:35.000
And--and "Trust"
was my second film.

25:36.834 --> 25:39.000
- Come back here a minute.

25:39.083 --> 25:42.876
- First one was so much easier
for me to make,

25:42.959 --> 25:45.209
because it was closer
to who I actually am.

25:46.584 --> 25:50.292
She's your typical pregnant
high school teenager...

25:50.375 --> 25:53.542
- Whose baby?
- Yours, you jerk!

25:53.626 --> 25:55.584
- Who accidentally
kills her father

25:55.667 --> 25:57.292
in the first scene
of the movie.

26:00.042 --> 26:01.459
- She seemed
to be the centerpiece

26:01.542 --> 26:03.125
to a lot of Hal's films.

26:03.209 --> 26:06.125
I was like, "God, if--maybe
she's his muse in a way."

26:06.209 --> 26:08.918
And there was something kind of
ethereal about Adrienne.

26:09.000 --> 26:11.918
I mean,
she looked like a doll.

26:12.000 --> 26:13.584
- It was just young people
learning the ropes

26:13.667 --> 26:15.209
of being
in the entertainment business

26:15.292 --> 26:16.918
and some of the uglier parts
of it.

26:17.000 --> 26:19.459
And also very good parts too.

26:21.167 --> 26:23.918
By the time we arrived
in Toronto

26:24.000 --> 26:27.334
for the opening night premiere
of "Trust,"

26:27.417 --> 26:28.876
she was kind of a star.

26:28.959 --> 26:31.626
[Blondie's "Dreaming"]

26:55.167 --> 26:59.292
-  When I met you
in a restaurant

26:59.375 --> 27:00.626
- When you're starting out
as an actor,

27:00.709 --> 27:03.626
the odds of something like
what happened to Adrienne...

27:03.709 --> 27:04.834
- Right, she was,
like, an overnight--

27:04.918 --> 27:06.167
- Happening so, so fast--
yes.

27:06.250 --> 27:10.167
And she was very conflicted
about it as well,

27:10.250 --> 27:12.417
because it is overwhelming.

27:12.500 --> 27:14.876
I mean, suddenly she's on the
cover of "Interview" magazine,

27:14.959 --> 27:18.709
and filmmakers are calling
her, and she just--

27:18.792 --> 27:21.209
I don't think she was prepared
for how big--

27:21.292 --> 27:24.334
I don't think anyone was--how
big that film was going to be.

27:25.167 --> 27:29.209
-  Dreaming, dreaming

27:29.292 --> 27:32.834
- After we premiered "Trust,"
she immediately went to LA

27:32.918 --> 27:34.042
to do a movie.

27:34.125 --> 27:37.792
She was getting
really good roles.

27:37.876 --> 27:40.834
- I really like it.
- What?

27:40.918 --> 27:43.209
- Your work.

27:43.292 --> 27:46.459
Reminds me
of a dream I once had.

27:47.918 --> 27:52.209
- Stephanie,
that's just a blank canvas.

27:54.292 --> 27:55.834
- Yeah.

27:57.792 --> 28:00.584
- There was one--
some sort of glamorous opening

28:00.667 --> 28:02.292
that she was invited to,
and she took us,

28:02.375 --> 28:03.834
and all of these people--
really, she was, like,

28:03.918 --> 28:05.918
their darling,
and she really didn't want

28:06.000 --> 28:07.334
that much to do with it.

28:09.959 --> 28:12.334
- Hi, everybody.
- She was a little dismissive

28:12.417 --> 28:14.959
of the movies she was making.

28:15.042 --> 28:16.334
They were a means to an end.

28:16.417 --> 28:18.375
- She did a lot
of really crappy movies...

28:18.459 --> 28:20.042
- Yeah, yeah.
- In the '90s.

28:20.125 --> 28:24.500
None of them really
showcased who she was.

28:24.584 --> 28:26.167
- Well, a lot of times,
they liked to showcase her

28:26.250 --> 28:27.209
as the sexpot.

28:27.292 --> 28:30.709
- Right.
- And as sexy as Adrienne was,

28:30.792 --> 28:32.584
that's not her persona.

28:33.083 --> 28:37.918
- I have a--you know, a certain
interest in self-respect

28:38.000 --> 28:42.959
