and that's him.

41:35.292 --> 41:39.459
"Diego Pillco, you'll
probably recognize my name.

41:39.542 --> 41:41.334
"I'm Adrienne Shelly's
husband.

41:41.417 --> 41:44.042
"11 years has passed
since that fateful day

41:44.125 --> 41:45.751
"in November 2006.

41:45.834 --> 41:49.042
"So many lives profoundly
changed that day,

41:49.125 --> 41:51.626
"including yours.

41:51.709 --> 41:53.250
"Not a minute
of every day goes by

41:53.334 --> 41:56.292
"without me thinking of
Adrienne and what I've lost,

41:56.375 --> 42:00.250
"what my daughter Sophie,
who is now 14, has lost,

42:00.334 --> 42:02.459
"what the world has lost.

42:02.542 --> 42:05.918
"I would like to talk with you
about what happened that day.

42:06.000 --> 42:08.709
Will you agree to meet
and talk with me?"

42:14.792 --> 42:16.918
- Oh!
- Ow, watch where you're--

42:17.000 --> 42:18.334
Hey.
- Hey, hi, Adrienne.

42:18.417 --> 42:19.542
- Hi, Tim.
- Good to see you.

42:19.626 --> 42:21.209
- Good to see you too.
- Hey, what are you doing?

42:21.292 --> 42:22.542
- Oh, I don't know--
- Do you have a minute

42:22.626 --> 42:24.375
to talk
about "Sudden Manhattan"?

42:24.459 --> 42:27.709
- I certainly have a minute to
talk about "Sudden Manhattan."

42:27.792 --> 42:30.792
Six, seven, eight.

42:30.876 --> 42:32.792
Eight zits.

42:32.876 --> 42:35.083
One less than yesterday.

42:35.167 --> 42:36.626
What happened
to the missing zit?

42:36.709 --> 42:39.250
Where'd it go?

42:39.334 --> 42:40.626
Hmm.

42:40.709 --> 42:42.626
One zit less.

42:45.626 --> 42:47.083
Well,
I wanted to make this movie

42:47.167 --> 42:49.250
because I think
it's sort of an analogy

42:49.334 --> 42:52.417
to being in your 20s, being
at a certain point in your life

42:52.500 --> 42:55.918
where, you know, a lot of
strange things are happening

42:56.000 --> 42:57.918
to you and you can't
really make any sense of--

42:58.000 --> 42:59.584
of them.

43:01.834 --> 43:04.834
I'm stuck in a vortex.

43:04.918 --> 43:07.709
I'm stuck
in a vortex.

43:07.792 --> 43:12.000
It's really about, uh,
trying to find meaning

43:12.083 --> 43:15.667
in a world
that is often very confusing.

43:15.751 --> 43:17.876
- And then she steals
the carrot out of my mouth,

43:17.959 --> 43:20.500
and she hop, hop, hops away.

43:20.584 --> 43:24.375
And my voice tells me,
"Bonnie, you dumb bunny.

43:24.459 --> 43:26.667
She wants you to follow."

43:26.751 --> 43:29.250
[distorted] Then he took
the gun and shot the man dead

43:29.334 --> 43:30.792
in plain daylight.

43:30.876 --> 43:31.959
- That film was nuts, right?

43:32.042 --> 43:33.292
Like, what did you think of it?
- It was nuts.

43:33.375 --> 43:35.459
Like, it always amazed me,
Adrienne would say,

43:35.542 --> 43:38.000
"I'm writing this thing,"
then suddenly she would call

43:38.083 --> 43:41.417
three weeks later
and say, "We have funding."

43:41.500 --> 43:42.500
I don't know how it happened.
- Right.

43:42.584 --> 43:44.626
- It just--somehow,
she knew someone and knew--

43:44.709 --> 43:47.626
and she just got on the phone
and worked connections

43:47.709 --> 43:49.751
and called people,
and they read her work

43:49.834 --> 43:51.042
and liked it,
so they produced it.

43:52.417 --> 43:54.334
- Tea leaves, palm readings,
aura readings,

43:54.417 --> 43:57.375
tarot cards, astrology,
past life readings,

43:57.459 --> 44:00.375
or guardian angel information.

44:00.459 --> 44:02.542
- Uh, no, I don't--
I don't think--

44:02.626 --> 44:05.459
- Or I can do all of them
at the same time.

44:05.542 --> 44:07.417
- You do all of them
at the same time?

44:07.500 --> 44:08.417
- Mm-hmm.

44:08.500 --> 44:10.042
- I think it was
"Sudden Manhattan,"

44:10.125 --> 44:13.500
and she was having a lot of
difficulty with the reception,

44:13.584 --> 44:16.334
and she got a negative review
somewhere,

44:16.417 --> 44:17.876
and she called me.

44:20.083 --> 44:22.083
And she was just crying...

44:22.167 --> 44:24.834
- No reason
to get out of bed.

44:24.918 --> 44:26.292
- For several hours,

44:26.375 --> 44:29.000
because somebody had
ripped her to shreds.

44:29.083 --> 44:32.083
- No reason to brush my teeth.

44:32.167 --> 44:33.918
- What Adrienne found
in making that movie

44:34.000 --> 44:37.083
is that being in the movie,
writing it, and directing it,

44:37.167 --> 44:40.417
critics were not going to be
kind to a woman who did that.

44:40.500 --> 44:43.000
- Right.
- And I really do feel

44:43.083 --> 44:46.626
there was tremendous sexism
that made that

44:46.709 --> 44:48.709
a hard thing to do.

44:48.792 --> 44:51.542
[dramatic romantic music]

44:53.292 --> 44:55.626
[doorbell rings]

44:55.709 --> 44:57.542
- Mahjong.

44:57.626 --> 44:59.417
all: Mahjong!

44:59.500 --> 45:01.792
- I said to her,
"Tell me about this character.

45:01.876 --> 45:05.083
I mean, what are you really
looking for?"

45:05.167 --> 45:06.918
What I wanna know is...

45:08.417 --> 45:12.250
Do you wanna go to Spain
with me and make love?

45:12.334 --> 45:14.000
And she said, "Well," she said

45:14.083 --> 45:16.125
"This character's really based
on my mother."

45:16.209 --> 45:17.542
- You know Missy.
- Hi, Lois.

45:17.626 --> 45:19.292
- Missy's taking Mona's place
in the mahjong game.

45:19.375 --> 45:21.792
- How's it going?

45:21.876 --> 45:23.626
- It's--
it's going well.

45:23.709 --> 45:26.209
- Yeah?
- Yeah, I'm having a good time.

45:26.292 --> 45:28.792
Somebody's agreed
to let me make a movie again.

45:28.876 --> 45:30.834
And that's, um--

45:30.918 --> 45:33.709
that never, you know,
fails to surprise me

45:33.792 --> 45:35.751
and delight me.

45:35.834 --> 45:37.542
It's called
"Get Up and Recover."

45:37.626 --> 45:38.834
- Oh, Lucy.

45:38.918 --> 45:41.334
- There are all
these great exercises in here,

45:41.417 --> 45:45.209
not just to, um...
forget your misery

45:45.292 --> 45:49.417
but to go forward,
to face your pain.

45:49.500 --> 45:51.375
You know,
to strengthen your soul.

45:51.459 --> 45:52.709
- There's nothing wrong
with my soul.

45:52.792 --> 45:56.209
- This is exactly the situation
that life offers you

45:56.292 --> 45:59.000
a real opportunity to grow.

45:59.083 --> 46:02.167
There's--there's not really
one breakup in particular

46:02.250 --> 46:04.292
that inspired this film.

46:04.375 --> 46:07.667
I think I've probably been
all of the characters

46:07.751 --> 46:09.626
in the film
at one time or another.

46:09.709 --> 46:12.500
I set up a date for you.

46:12.584 --> 46:15.292
- Are you kidding?
- With Bernice.

46:15.375 --> 46:18.083
My friend from college,
she just moved here from LA.

46:18.167 --> 46:19.417
- You did what?

46:19.500 --> 46:21.542
- You told me
you thought she was cute.

46:21.626 --> 46:25.167
- That was eight years ago.
I met her for five minutes.

46:25.250 --> 46:26.459
- Bill, you gotta move forward.

46:26.542 --> 46:27.626
You gotta move forward, Bill.

46:27.709 --> 46:30.584
- I can't go on a date, Lucy.
I can't tie my shoes.

46:30.667 --> 46:32.959
What are you talking about,
a date?

46:33.042 --> 46:34.792
Cancel it.
- I can't.

46:34.876 --> 46:37.459
- Why not?
[doorbell buzzes]

46:39.417 --> 46:40.751
- Hi.

46:40.834 --> 46:45.834
- I was going for a tone
in the film where--

46:45.918 --> 46:50.709
where you can kind of find
what's funny in what's painful.

46:50.792 --> 46:52.167
Um, which has always kind of

46:52.250 --> 46:54.751
been my strategy anyway
in life, you know.

46:54.834 --> 46:57.834
I think it's a great
sort of survival technique.

47:00.709 --> 47:02.667
- "Oddly enough,
I believe that the person

47:02.751 --> 47:05.000
"who's had the greatest
influence on my creative life

47:05.083 --> 47:06.626
has been my father."

47:08.083 --> 47:09.375
"The reason why this is unusual

47:09.459 --> 47:12.334
"is that I have not
seen my father in 18 years.

47:12.417 --> 47:14.876
"He died very suddenly
when I was 12.

47:14.959 --> 47:16.667
"He was 40 years old.

47:16.751 --> 47:18.209
"This was to begin my strange

47:18.292 --> 47:20.417
"and ugly companionship
with grief.

47:20.500 --> 47:22.667
"Learning to cope with loss
has been an odyssey

47:22.751 --> 47:24.167
for me throughout my life."

47:24.250 --> 47:26.626
- One of the most
incredible moments

47:26.709 --> 47:28.834
I ever had with Adrienne

47:28.918 --> 47:31.667
was when she told me

47:31.751 --> 47:33.292
what she remembered
from that day.

47:33.375 --> 47:34.959
- From when her father--
[gasps]

47:35.042 --> 47:36.292
And what was that?

47:36.375 --> 47:38.584
- She was picked up at camp.
- Right, right.

47:38.667 --> 47:41.709
- She said it was a--
a long ride home,

47:41.792 --> 47:43.375
and she literally was
staring out the window,

47:43.459 --> 47:46.250
wondering, "What is going on?"

47:46.334 --> 47:48.667
And she said,
"I went into the house,

47:48.751 --> 47:51.083
"and I walked into the kitchen,

47:51.167 --> 47:53.834
"and on the kitchen table

47:53.918 --> 47:55.751
was an obituary
from the newspaper."

47:55.834 --> 47:57.334
- [gasps]
Oh!

47:57.417 --> 48:00.125
- So here--here's--
here's the incredible part.

48:00.209 --> 48:02.876
She faked not knowing...

48:02.959 --> 48:04.292
- Yeah.
- Because she didn't want...

48:04.375 --> 48:06.125
- Oh.
- To make you feel bad.

48:06.209 --> 48:09.792
The way she told me this story,
she started laughing.

48:09.876 --> 48:11.792
And she said to me,
"Can you believe this?

48:11.876 --> 48:14.459
This is how I found out
how my father died."

48:15.334 --> 48:20.083
The tonal shift is really
what she brought to her work.

48:20.167 --> 48:22.459
Just the horror and the comedy

48:22.542 --> 48:26.459
all wrapped
into one crazy moment.

48:26.542 --> 48:29.417
- "When loss--the fear of it
as well as the truth of it--

48:29.500 --> 48:32.250
"runs your life, there is not
much room in your life

48:32.334 --> 48:34.542
for other things, like love."

48:47.918 --> 48:50.042
That's it.
- That's it?

48:50.125 --> 48:51.500
- Yes.
- No more?

48:51.584 --> 48:53.042
- No.
- Did you have fun?

48:53.125 --> 48:55.000
- Yes.
- Yeah, is that a fun car?

48:55.083 --> 48:57.876
- Yes.
- Why is it fun?

48:57.959 --> 48:59.584
- Because you bought it.

48:59.667 --> 49:00.792
- Because I bought it?

49:00.876 --> 49:01.959
- Yes.
- Oh, that's nice.

49:02.042 --> 49:03.292
So are you a good driver?

49:03.375 --> 49:05.500
- Good job.

49:05.584 --> 49:07.417
- I think it was about
three weeks later, maybe--

49:07.500 --> 49:10.083
no, a month later.

49:10.167 --> 49:11.959
You--
you wanted to get Sophie--

49:12.042 --> 49:13.167
you got--you just wanted
to get her out of--

49:13.250 --> 49:14.334
you needed to get
out of New York.

49:14.417 --> 49:15.792
And you came to visit.

49:16.751 --> 49:19.626
I remember opening the door
and--and...

49:19.709 --> 49:21.834
you and Sophie walking
up the walkway there,

49:21.918 --> 49:23.709
opening the gate.

49:23.792 --> 49:25.334
And I remember...

49:26.959 --> 49:28.918
It wasn't three of you.
It was two of you.

49:30.500 --> 49:33.792
- I had a lot of people
who would say things

49:33.876 --> 49:35.250
like, "Everything's
gonna be okay,"

49:35.334 --> 49:36.375
"You'll get through it,"

49:36.459 --> 49:38.751
all the things
that nice people say

49:38.834 --> 49:42.209
when they care about you and
want to make you feel better.

49:42.292 --> 49:43.417
I remember this one guy

49:43.500 --> 49:46.500
whose son committed suicide
many years earlier,

49:46.584 --> 49:49.918
and then he contacted me
right away, and he was like,

49:50.000 --> 49:51.042
"Here's what's gonna
happen day one.

49:51.125 --> 49:53.125
"Here's what's gonna happen
month one, month two,

49:53.209 --> 49:54.417
year one, year two."

49:54.500 --> 49:55.834
He laid out, like, a blueprint

49:55.918 --> 49:57.500
of, like, how often I'll cry.

49:57.584 --> 49:59.334
I found that invaluable.

49:59.417 --> 50:02.000
Uh, my friend Julie Rudd,

50:02.083 --> 50:05.918
uh, had a fiancé who died
in a horrible work accident.

50:06.000 --> 50:08.375
- I think it might
have been a week later

50:08.459 --> 50:10.417
that you called me,
and I was like,

50:10.500 --> 50:14.083
"Oh, he--this is--he's--
he's gonna be okay,

50:14.167 --> 50:18.918
"because he is already looking
to climb himself out.

50:19.000 --> 50:21.626
"You know, he doesn't
wanna stay where he is,

50:21.709 --> 50:25.042
and he knows he can't, because
he's got a young daughter."

50:25.125 --> 50:28.542
- Was there ever a moment
where...

50:28.626 --> 50:32.042
you didn't think you would
be able to move on from this?

50:32.125 --> 50:33.417
- No.

50:34.667 --> 50:36.500
No, not in that sense.

50:36.584 --> 50:38.876
But I had really dark moments--

50:38.959 --> 50:40.709
dark, dark, dark moments,

50:40.792 --> 50:43.709
going in that closet
in the back,

50:43.792 --> 50:46.792
taking her clothes
and curling up on a--

50:46.876 --> 50:49.792
fetal position on the floor
and just sobbing

50:49.876 --> 50:52.709
till I literally
had nothing left.

50:52.792 --> 50:55.959
But then over, you know,
the next few days,

50:56.042 --> 50:59.083
the next week, two weeks,
three weeks, four weeks,

50:59.167 --> 51:02.792
all of a sudden, you know,
a routine settles in.

51:02.876 --> 51:05.250
I just looked at her
and made her a promise

51:05.334 --> 51:09.209
that she's gonna grow up happy
and healthy.

51:09.292 --> 51:11.417
We're gonna be okay.

51:11.500 --> 51:13.918
Like, we're a team.
We're gonna be okay.

51:14.000 --> 51:16.918
[soft music]

51:19.042 --> 51:21.626
- I don't want you
to be sad, okay, Daddy?

51:21.709 --> 51:23.584
- You think Daddy looks sad?
- Yes.

51:23.667 --> 51:26.125
But I'm gonna take care
of you when Mommy died.

51:26.209 --> 51:28.167
- I'm so lucky to have you.

51:29.375 --> 51:30.667
- You be so proud of me,

51:30.751 --> 51:33.834
and you not be sad anymore
that Mommy died.

51:33.918 --> 51:36.167
I like Mommy's picture
up there.

51:36.250 --> 51:38.792
- Mommy's watching over her
little girl while she sleeps.

51:38.876 --> 51:40.667
- She's watching me?
- Yes.

51:40.751 --> 51:43.334
She'll always be with you,
everywhere you go.

51:54.167 --> 51:56.250
How do you feel about,
like, today

51:56.334 --> 51:59.083
versus other days?

52:00.542 --> 52:03.125
- It doesn't really
feel very different

52:03.209 --> 52:06.334
than most days, like,
'cause it's just a day,

52:06.417 --> 52:08.125
but it just happens to be,
like, when--

52:08.209 --> 52:10.042
like,
an anniversary of something,

52:10.125 --> 52:13.209
so it's, like,
always in the back of my mind.

52:13.292 --> 52:15.709
It's not like
it's harder today.

52:15.792 --> 52:18.209
I think it's only harder

52:18.292 --> 52:21.542
because
I'm thinking about it more

52:21.626 --> 52:23.792
than I would
on a different day.

52:23.876 --> 52:26.918
- Are there days
or holidays in particular

52:27.000 --> 52:29.167
more so than other days
or other holidays

52:29.250 --> 52:31.000
that make you think more
about that?

52:31.083 --> 52:33.792
- Well, Halloween,
'cause it's right there,

52:33.876 --> 52:35.334
and the party you guys threw.

52:35.417 --> 52:38.542
- Mm-hmm.
- Um, Mother's Day, obviously.

52:38.626 --> 52:39.792
- Mm-hmm.
- Um--

52:39.876 --> 52:43.209
- What do you typically feel
on Mother's Day?

52:43.292 --> 52:46.667
- Um, just kind of like, um,

52:46.751 --> 52:48.834
like, robbed.

52:48.918 --> 52:50.918
Like, I'm just jealous all day.

52:51.000 --> 52:53.584
Just 'cause of,
like, other people

52:53.667 --> 52:55.417
and, like, their moms.

52:55.500 --> 52:57.667
Like, I'm jealous of that.

52:57.751 --> 53:00.209
I'm understanding now
how permanent it is.

53:00.292 --> 53:01.626
- Mm-hmm.
- That's hard to deal with,

53:01.709 --> 53:05.417
but it's mostly just like,
I'm never going to have one.

53:05.500 --> 53:08.292
Like, the permanency of that.
- Mm-hmm.

53:18.959 --> 53:21.375
- Hi.

53:21.459 --> 53:25.375
It's me, Adrienne, and, uh--

53:25.459 --> 53:28.375
and I just started shooting
this documentary

53:28.459 --> 53:30.042
a few days ago.

53:30.125 --> 53:32.459
- One of the things
that I've discovered

53:32.542 --> 53:34.792
through this process
is, Adrienne--

53:34.876 --> 53:35.834
and maybe you know about it,
Adrienne was

53:35.918 --> 53:37.417
making a documentary
about happiness.

53:37.500 --> 53:38.792
Do you know anything
about that?

53:38.876 --> 53:43.292
-  There's too many things
I haven't done yet

53:43.375 --> 53:46.834
There's too many sunsets

53:46.918 --> 53:50.834
I haven't seen

53:50.918 --> 53:55.375
You can't waste the day
wishing it'd slow down

53:55.459 --> 53:58.542
You would've thought
by now

53:58.626 --> 53:59.542
- I have the tapes.

53:59.626 --> 54:00.667
- That's amazing.
- And they're amazing.

54:00.751 --> 54:03.918
[Sara Bareilles'
"Many the Miles"]

54:04.000 --> 54:05.709
[doorbell rings]

54:05.792 --> 54:08.417
- We're making a--
a documentary about happiness.

54:08.500 --> 54:10.584
I'm assuming you're a couple.
- We are.

54:10.667 --> 54:12.459
- We're--we're actually looking
for the happiest person

54:12.542 --> 54:13.792
in New York.

54:13.876 --> 54:16.500
- We're pretty happy.
Erica makes me happy.

54:16.584 --> 54:18.375
- Aww.
This is for you.

54:18.459 --> 54:19.918
- What is--this is for me?
- It's a yo-yo.

54:20.000 --> 54:22.959
- Oh, how very nice.
I shall play with this at home.

54:23.042 --> 54:24.667
[laughter]

54:24.751 --> 54:27.792
- We went, uh, my boyfriend
and I, to see, um...

54:27.876 --> 54:29.459
Burt Bacharach
and Elvis Costello

54:29.542 --> 54:31.167
in concert at Carnegie Hall.

54:31.250 --> 54:32.667
I used to come here
for breakfast--

54:32.751 --> 54:35.334
it was a breakfast place--
with my ex-boyfriend.

54:35.417 --> 54:37.500
And, uh, it was really painful
because we knew

54:37.584 --> 54:40.292
that we were gonna end
our relationship that night.

54:40.375 --> 54:42.167
We used to fight a lot here.

54:42.250 --> 54:45.000
We were just kind of
frozen there in our seats

54:45.083 --> 54:47.626
listening to them sing
this stuff.

54:47.709 --> 54:50.000
And then finally,
uh, we broke up here.

54:50.083 --> 54:53.709
And I remember feeling like,
"Ugh, yeah, pain!

54:53.792 --> 54:56.375
Ugh, yeah, life--
give it to me, give it to me."

54:56.459 --> 55:00.042
And the place, uh, was a place
I think of misery and failure

55:00.125 --> 55:02.125
for the owners also, 'cause
they went out of business,

55:02.209 --> 55:05.209
and it became
another restaurant altogether.

55:05.292 --> 55:07.709
We were very specifically
looking for a restaurant

55:07.792 --> 55:09.709
to break up in,
and finally, uh,

55:09.792 --> 55:14.209
we settled into
Ollie's Noodle Shop and Grill.

55:14.292 --> 55:18.459
I came back, um, with a--
with a new boyfriend,

55:18.542 --> 55:21.250
and, uh--and he broke up
with me here too.

55:21.334 --> 55:22.834
I listened to him
tell me everything

55:22.918 --> 55:25.834
that was wrong with me
and how I had failed him.

55:25.918 --> 55:27.667
And then shortly after that,

55:27.751 --> 55:30.167
uh, that restaurant
went out of business.

55:30.250 --> 55:32.834
And I sat there and told him
everything that he did wrong

55:32.918 --> 55:35.292
and how he failed me.

55:35.375 --> 55:39.292
And, uh--and it was just--
it was just awful.

55:39.375 --> 55:43.209
So I try to stay away from here
if I can,

55:43.292 --> 55:47.292
um, not bring any beaus here,

55:47.375 --> 55:50.042
because they're just
gonna break up with me,

55:50.125 --> 55:52.125
and--and then
the restaurant's gonna close.

55:52.209 --> 55:54.959
- She had so many
crappy relationships.

55:55.042 --> 55:58.042
- So many, so many.
- I often think about, like,

55:58.125 --> 55:59.500
she was smart,
she was beautiful.

55:59.584 --> 56:01.876
Like,
she had everything to offer.

56:01.959 --> 56:03.876
- I want, you know,
very different things now

56:03.959 --> 56:06.250
than when I was younger.

56:06.334 --> 56:09.042
And I'd like to think that,
you know, I could...

56:11.792 --> 56:15.709
Spend my life with somebody
and have a family and, uh--

56:15.792 --> 56:20.417
and still be allowed
to be myself, you know?

56:20.500 --> 56:21.792
- And was it just the--
- I think

56:21.876 --> 56:24.626
that a lot of men

56:24.709 --> 56:30.125
felt that here was this tiny,
little, adorable woman

56:30.209 --> 56:33.292
that they were going
to take care of

56:33.375 --> 56:36.167
and protect and control.

56:36.250 --> 56:39.250
And she had no intention
of that happening.

56:39.334 --> 56:43.375
She was tiny
but very large in personality

56:43.459 --> 56:47.876
and in mind and in deed
and in will.

56:47.959 --> 56:49.792
- Are you in love?

56:49.876 --> 56:51.000
- No.
I'm in love,

56:51.083 --> 56:52.584
but, um, I don't know with--

56:52.667 --> 56:53.918
I mean,
he's somewhere out there.

56:54.000 --> 56:55.083
I don't know where he is.

56:55.167 --> 56:57.167
I'm--I have all this love
inside of me

56:57.250 --> 57:00.083
and no one to give it to now.

57:00.167 --> 57:02.626
- And because I'm--
I'm on this sort of quest

57:02.709 --> 57:05.792
to figure out what happiness
is in this documentary,

57:05.876 --> 57:11.500
I guess I--I should...
probably admit that, uh,

57:11.584 --> 57:15.667
I--I'm not really
such an expert on it.

57:17.083 --> 57:19.834
- The conversation that we used
to have quite a bit

57:19.918 --> 57:21.709
is, what's more important
to us?

57:21.792 --> 57:24.500
Is having love and marriage
more important to us?

57:24.584 --> 57:27.417
Or is it more im--is our art
more important to us?

57:27.500 --> 57:29.417
And we would have those debates
a lot.

57:29.500 --> 57:33.459
And Adrienne fell into the camp
of, "Love and marriage

57:33.542 --> 57:36.167
is ultimately more important
to me."

57:36.250 --> 57:39.167
- Are you happy?
- I'm content.

57:39.250 --> 57:41.167
- Knowing her
and knowing how passionate

57:41.250 --> 57:43.709
about her work she was,
I was surprised.

57:43.792 --> 57:46.250
But thinking back on it,
I'm not.

57:46.334 --> 57:48.876
- "I want love to work.
I want no more pain.

57:48.959 --> 57:50.876
"I want to have a child
and a family.

57:50.959 --> 57:53.250
"I want to create marvelous
things from my heart and mind

57:53.334 --> 57:55.042
and hands and mouth."

57:55.125 --> 57:57.042
- I remember when I first came
to New York,

57:57.125 --> 57:59.000
when I first moved to New York,
I--

57:59.083 --> 58:01.375
I, um--
I--I--

58:01.459 --> 58:03.042
I said the same kind of thing
to myself,

58:03.125 --> 58:04.751
that, you know,
he's somewhere here.

58:04.834 --> 58:06.792
- He has to be.
- Wonder where he is

58:06.876 --> 58:08.000
and what he's doing right now

58:08.083 --> 58:10.584
and if he's wondering
where I am, you know.

58:11.459 --> 58:16.209
I want to be part of something
that's bigger than just me.

58:18.375 --> 58:19.959
- She wanted to be loved.

58:20.042 --> 58:24.083
You know, talking to her a few
late nights where she really

58:24.167 --> 58:25.876
had the feeling
she would never be loved

58:25.959 --> 58:27.125
and it would never happen.

58:27.209 --> 58:29.918
And I knew
that was literally impossible.

58:30.000 --> 58:31.959
This is just
what's happening now.

58:32.042 --> 58:33.792
That person is out there.

58:33.876 --> 58:36.250
And of course he was,
and it was you.

58:39.000 --> 58:42.584
- She met you, um,
as I believe, after 9/11.

58:42.667 --> 58:44.459
You were volunteering downtown.

58:44.542 --> 58:45.626
- No, no, no, no.
- She said she met you

58:45.709 --> 58:47.584
at a political fundraiser.

58:47.667 --> 58:49.209
- What?
She said to me,

58:49.292 --> 58:51.417
you know, like a lot of people
after 9/11,

58:51.500 --> 58:52.876
you know, you start
reassessing your life.

58:52.959 --> 58:54.334
- Right.
- Like, "What am I doing?"

58:54.417 --> 58:55.500
- So it was after 9/11?
- It was right after--

58:55.584 --> 58:56.542
- So I got that part right?
- Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

58:56.626 --> 58:58.083
- She told me that you guys met

58:58.167 --> 59:01.125
at a political fundraiser.

59:01.209 --> 59:03.876
- Did you volunteer
with her after together?

59:03.959 --> 59:05.000
- She told me she went
on Match,

59:05.083 --> 59:06.209
and she was embarrassed.

59:06.292 --> 59:08.584
She was a little, like,
"I don't want anyone to know."

59:08.667 --> 59:10.209
Hi, now everybody knows.

59:10.292 --> 59:11.959
I supported her instantly.
I said, "Great.

59:12.042 --> 59:14.167
"That's how people--
you know, it's--you know,

59:14.250 --> 59:15.667
people meet people
that way now."

59:15.751 --> 59:17.876
I mean,
it's a great way to get outside

59:17.959 --> 59:20.083
of the sphere
of just show business.

59:20.167 --> 59:23.083
And she made it clear, like,
"I only went to one person.

59:23.167 --> 59:27.459
I saw his profile picture,
I chose it, and that was that."

59:27.542 --> 59:29.959
She made one connection.
It was you.

59:30.042 --> 59:33.250
- Listen, um, I have a
five-minute blind date tonight

59:33.334 --> 59:35.292
with an insurance salesman
named Pete--

59:35.375 --> 59:39.167
5'10", 37, all his hair,
nice picture, loves fishin'.

59:39.250 --> 59:40.167
- Five-minute date?

59:40.250 --> 59:41.542
Can't the guy pay
for the whole thing?

59:41.626 --> 59:42.959
- She literally said to me,

59:43.042 --> 59:44.834
"We're gonna go
on a five-minute date."

59:45.542 --> 59:47.626
That was the first time
I heard that idea.

59:47.709 --> 59:49.375
And I said,
"How does that work?"

59:49.459 --> 59:50.959
She explained the whole thing.

59:51.042 --> 59:53.500
She said, "I show up,
I look at you, you look at me,

59:53.584 --> 59:55.209
"and we talk for five minutes,
we hate each other.

59:55.292 --> 59:57.542
Like, why--what's the point
of staying, like, longer?"

59:57.626 --> 59:59.709
And we sat there
for five hours.

59:59.792 --> 1:00:01.876
The five-minute date
became five hours.

1:00:03.250 --> 1:00:05.584
- I got a secret too.

1:00:05.667 --> 1:00:07.375
- You, Dawn?
- Yes.

1:00:07.459 --> 1:00:08.959
I have a boyfriend now.
- [gasps]

1:00:09.042 --> 1:00:11.209
- No.
- Yes.

1:00:11.292 --> 1:00:14.125
- It really did feel different
from all the other guys.

1:00:14.209 --> 1:00:16.626
And she said,
"You know, I can't believe it,

1:00:16.709 --> 1:00:20.125
but my dream guy is, like,
a divorced dad of three."

1:00:20.209 --> 1:00:21.959
- I'm happy to say
I loved you right away.

1:00:22.042 --> 1:00:23.792
Um, you had good hair.

1:00:23.876 --> 1:00:26.167
- I just remember how excited
you were and how surprised

1:00:26.250 --> 1:00:28.834
I was that somebody like her
was going out with you.

1:00:28.918 --> 1:00:30.042
- You said, "You're
dating Adrienne Shelly?"

1:00:30.125 --> 1:00:32.918
And I said, "Yeah," and you
said, "The Adrienne Shelly?"

1:00:33.000 --> 1:00:36.709
And I said, "Yeah," and then
you--and then you said,

1:00:36.792 --> 1:00:38.375
"The Hal Hartley
Adrienne Shelly?

1:00:38.459 --> 1:00:39.918
'Trust' Adrienne Shelly?"

1:00:40.000 --> 1:00:43.751
And then you said, "Ostroy,

1:00:43.834 --> 1:00:46.000
"most days,
I feel sorry for you.

1:00:46.083 --> 1:00:47.334
Today's not one of 'em."

1:00:47.417 --> 1:00:49.042
[laughter]

1:00:49.125 --> 1:00:51.709
Not only was she just
brilliant and funny,

1:00:51.792 --> 1:00:57.042
but she was absolutely the
cutest thing I had ever met.

1:00:57.125 --> 1:01:00.500
I really felt like I was in the
presence of someone special.

1:01:00.584 --> 1:01:03.334
Like this was the person
I was intended to be with

1:01:03.417 --> 1:01:05.167
for the rest of my life--
my soul mate.

1:01:05.250 --> 1:01:06.834
All the cheesy stuff.

1:01:06.918 --> 1:01:09.709
[jaunty accordion music]

1:01:18.834 --> 1:01:20.459
Who is this crazy lady?

1:01:20.542 --> 1:01:22.792
- It's so big.

1:01:22.876 --> 1:01:26.209
- I just got an Eiffel Tower
for one euro,

1:01:26.292 --> 1:01:27.751
but he gave me another one
for free.

1:01:27.834 --> 1:01:29.876
- Ooh, cool.
- So nice.

1:01:31.125 --> 1:01:33.792
- I proposed to her that
following summer in Paris.

1:01:36.667 --> 1:01:39.375
I carried the ring with me
everywhere we went.

1:01:40.459 --> 1:01:41.918
- So how did you propose?

1:01:42.000 --> 1:01:43.876
Like, was it a surprise?
Did you walk up--

1:01:43.959 --> 1:01:46.209
- Well,
we walked up this street,

1:01:46.292 --> 1:01:48.751
and I told your mom
that ever since I met her,

1:01:48.834 --> 1:01:53.250
I'd been really happy
and I can't imagine

1:01:53.334 --> 1:01:54.500
my life without her.

1:01:56.626 --> 1:01:59.542
So after Daddy proposed,
we came down here.

1:02:00.792 --> 1:02:03.792
And we just sat here,
and we talked for, like, hours.

1:02:03.876 --> 1:02:04.876
And we'd start planning--

1:02:04.959 --> 1:02:06.709
this is where we planned
the wedding, right here.

1:02:06.792 --> 1:02:07.792
- Really?
- Yeah.

1:02:07.876 --> 1:02:10.792
[John Lennon's "Oh My Love"]

1:02:10.876 --> 1:02:13.167
-  Oh, my love

1:02:13.250 --> 1:02:17.709
For the first time
in my life

1:02:17.792 --> 1:02:21.459
My eyes are wide open

1:02:21.542 --> 1:02:23.209
- When I first spoke
with everyone I knew

1:02:23.292 --> 1:02:25.417
about the man I was falling
in love with,

1:02:25.500 --> 1:02:30.292
who had been married twice
before and has three children,

1:02:30.375 --> 1:02:32.751
I braced myself for skepticism.

1:02:34.709 --> 1:02:37.125
But this is the mad,
crazy love affair

1:02:37.209 --> 1:02:39.500
I have waited for all my life.

1:02:39.584 --> 1:02:42.292
I vow to care
for your children,

1:02:42.375 --> 1:02:46.334
because they are a part of you
and an extra blessing to me.

1:02:46.417 --> 1:02:51.834
-  Everything is clear
in my heart

1:02:51.918 --> 1:02:54.167
- Yeah, when she called me,
I think she was so at peace

1:02:54.250 --> 1:02:57.792
that this other life that
she really actually wanted,

1:02:57.876 --> 1:02:59.000
she could have that too.

1:02:59.083 --> 1:03:00.792
She could--
she could do both.

1:03:00.876 --> 1:03:06.584
-  Everything is clear
in our world

1:03:06.667 --> 1:03:07.584
- I used to go over
to the house when I used

1:03:07.667 --> 1:03:09.125
to sleep over all the time,

1:03:09.209 --> 1:03:11.083
and Sophie would be on--
on the bed,

1:03:11.167 --> 1:03:13.375
and she would be changing,
and she would look,

1:03:13.459 --> 1:03:15.500
and she would say, "Ma,

1:03:15.584 --> 1:03:17.375
did you ever see a baby
like this, Ma?"

1:03:17.459 --> 1:03:20.209
The love that--I said,
"I know, I know, I know."

1:03:20.292 --> 1:03:24.083
And that's the thing
that she won't know.

1:03:24.167 --> 1:03:25.584
Sophie won't know this.

1:03:27.125 --> 1:03:29.167
- "April 7, 2004.

1:03:29.250 --> 1:03:31.876
"Dear Sophie,
you are nine weeks old today.

1:03:31.959 --> 1:03:34.083
"It's semi-crazy
how much I love you,

1:03:34.167 --> 1:03:36.542
"how you're so clearly
the best and most important

1:03:36.626 --> 1:03:38.918
"and realest thing
I've ever done.

1:03:39.000 --> 1:03:41.667
"Sometimes I well up with
tears just looking at you.

1:03:41.751 --> 1:03:43.500
"I have a ton of nicknames
for you:

1:03:43.584 --> 1:03:46.334
"Peanut, Monkey,
Chicken, Gumdrop,

1:03:46.417 --> 1:03:48.500
"Princess Boo-Boo, Soph-Soph.

1:03:48.584 --> 1:03:52.626
I love you so much--so much.
Mommy."

1:03:52.709 --> 1:03:55.209
"Happy first birthday.

1:03:55.292 --> 1:03:56.834
"My dear, sweet love bunny

1:03:56.918 --> 1:03:58.709
princess of the universe
Sophie,

1:03:58.792 --> 1:04:01.209
"you are meant to read this
when you are much older,

1:04:01.292 --> 1:04:03.375
"maybe 18, maybe 21.

1:04:03.459 --> 1:04:05.751
"At any rate,
when you are a woman.

1:04:05.834 --> 1:04:08.375
"So hard for me to believe
that you will be that someday.

1:04:08.459 --> 1:04:11.250
"Right now, you are delicious--
beyond delicious.

1:04:11.334 --> 1:04:12.792
"You are truly
the most beautiful baby

1:04:12.876 --> 1:04:13.959
"I have ever seen.

1:04:14.042 --> 1:04:16.584
"Your spirit is joyous,
and it is enormous.

1:04:16.667 --> 1:04:19.584
"I pray that you will keep
this amazing spirit always.

1:04:19.667 --> 1:04:22.292
"You are truly the light
of my life, my love.

1:04:22.375 --> 1:04:25.209
"You are nothing less than
the light of the whole world.

1:04:25.292 --> 1:04:26.876
"I could kiss you
a million times

1:04:26.959 --> 1:04:29.083
"and it would not
feel like enough.

1:04:29.167 --> 1:04:32.250
"Please take my love with you
wherever you go.

1:04:32.334 --> 1:04:34.167
"You hold my heart in yours.

1:04:34.250 --> 1:04:35.417
"My dearest, dearest Sophie,

1:04:35.500 --> 1:04:37.500
"I love you beyond words
to tell it.

1:04:37.584 --> 1:04:39.417
Your Mommy, XOXOXO."

1:04:39.500 --> 1:04:41.459
- Happy birthday, Sophie.

1:04:41.542 --> 1:04:43.250
Little Sophie.

1:04:43.334 --> 1:04:45.959
[somber music]

1:04:46.042 --> 1:04:47.959
- Who hurt Mommy?

1:04:48.042 --> 1:04:49.292
- A man.

1:04:49.375 --> 1:04:50.626
- What did he use
to hurt her?

1:04:50.709 --> 1:04:52.334
- His hands.

1:04:52.417 --> 1:04:54.709
- What's his name?
- Diego Pillco.

1:04:54.792 --> 1:04:56.667
- Where did she die?

1:04:56.751 --> 1:04:58.334
- Her office.
- Can we go there?

1:04:58.417 --> 1:05:00.459
- Why?
- To see Mommy.

1:05:00.542 --> 1:05:02.000
- But she's
not there anymore.

1:05:02.083 --> 1:05:03.918
- Where is she?
- She died, sweetie.

1:05:04.000 --> 1:05:06.709
Her body stopped working,
and she's not coming back.

1:05:27.417 --> 1:05:29.584
"Dear Mr. Ostroy,

1:05:29.667 --> 1:05:31.042
"I don't know how
to start this letter.

1:05:31.125 --> 1:05:33.626
"I'm surprised that you want
to talk to me.

1:05:33.709 --> 1:05:36.000
"I also would like
to talk with you.

1:05:36.083 --> 1:05:38.709
"I'm very"--
underlined--

1:05:38.792 --> 1:05:41.375
"very ashamed of myself

1:05:41.459 --> 1:05:45.292
"for what I did to you and your
family when I was a teenager.

1:05:45.375 --> 1:05:48.792
"Ashamed for the pain
I caused you and your daughter

1:05:48.876 --> 1:05:50.417
"and the rest of your family.

1:05:50.500 --> 1:05:51.959
"I'll carry this guilt
and remorse

1:05:52.042 --> 1:05:53.667
"for the rest of my life.

1:05:53.751 --> 1:05:55.500
"If at all possible,
could you let me know

1:05:55.584 --> 1:05:57.792
"what day you're planning
to come

1:05:57.876 --> 1:06:01.042
"so I can prepare myself
mentally?

1:06:01.125 --> 1:06:04.918
Because I'm very scared
and nervous."

1:06:13.000 --> 1:06:14.584
Um...

1:06:24.250 --> 1:06:26.250
He said yes.

1:06:28.751 --> 1:06:30.500
- I have a secret too.

1:06:30.584 --> 1:06:33.375
- You, Dawn?
- Yeah.

1:06:33.459 --> 1:06:35.459
I have a boyfriend now.

1:06:35.542 --> 1:06:36.918
- No.
- Yeah.

1:06:37.000 --> 1:06:38.000
- That's wonderful, honey.

1:06:38.083 --> 1:06:39.375
Who is he?
Tell us everything.

1:06:39.459 --> 1:06:40.876
- Oh, well,
you're never gonna believe it,

1:06:40.959 --> 1:06:43.000
but you know that guy who came
in the diner that time

1:06:43.083 --> 1:06:46.083
and he wouldn't leave--
name was Ogie?

1:06:46.167 --> 1:06:48.751
- Ogie, the stalking elf.
Yes, I remember that guy.

1:06:48.834 --> 1:06:50.250
What about him?

1:06:50.334 --> 1:06:52.500
[cheerful music]

1:06:52.584 --> 1:06:55.083
Adrienne was always writing.

1:06:55.167 --> 1:06:57.209
There's always a concept,
there's always a thing,

1:06:57.292 --> 1:07:00.584
there's always a--index cards
of the characters and--

1:07:00.667 --> 1:07:02.709
I used to see these things
all over the house

1:07:02.792 --> 1:07:03.918
and--
and say, "What is that?"

1:07:04.000 --> 1:07:05.250
"Eh, it's just something
I'm working on."

1:07:05.334 --> 1:07:08.709
Or, "That's an idea,
that's a"--always ideas.

1:07:08.792 --> 1:07:12.709
And then she said to me,
"I'm working on something

1:07:12.792 --> 1:07:16.542
"I really like, and I--
I think--

1:07:16.626 --> 1:07:18.375
I think has real potential."

1:07:18.459 --> 1:07:20.500
- Sorry, I don't want--
I won't do that anymore.

1:07:20.584 --> 1:07:22.334
You shouldn't be uncomfortable
during this time.

1:07:22.417 --> 1:07:23.876
- See,
and you're doing it again.

1:07:23.959 --> 1:07:25.167
- What am I doing?
- I don't know.

1:07:25.250 --> 1:07:29.125
I mean, you know, you do the--
the Mr. Nice Guy thing and--

1:07:29.209 --> 1:07:30.334
Forget it, forget it.

1:07:30.417 --> 1:07:31.459
- Good.
Okay.

1:07:31.542 --> 1:07:32.459
- I messed it up a little bit.

1:07:32.542 --> 1:07:34.042
- It's fine.
I don't care.

1:07:36.292 --> 1:07:38.667
- I was sort of like, "Why
doesn't she want to do this?"

1:07:38.751 --> 1:07:40.459
And she's like, "I wanna
direct it, I don't--you know."

1:07:40.542 --> 1:07:43.709
- The only time we ever
really worked together

1:07:43.792 --> 1:07:46.292
was trying to get "Waitress"
made and doing--

1:07:46.375 --> 1:07:47.834
- The reading.
- Doing the reading.

1:07:49.667 --> 1:07:51.876
It was apparent
even during the reading,

1:07:51.959 --> 1:07:56.125
she conjured everything,
and because she was an actor,

1:07:56.209 --> 1:07:58.792
she knew how to talk to actors.

1:07:58.876 --> 1:08:01.959
- You drop it here.
You come in, you rush in.

1:08:02.042 --> 1:08:04.792
- I think the biggest thing
about Adrienne, um,

1:08:04.876 --> 1:08:06.334
was, she really knew
what she wanted.

1:08:06.417 --> 1:08:08.125
She had such a clear idea
of it.

1:08:08.209 --> 1:08:10.459
- In this shot, we just
sit down in two and three.

1:08:10.542 --> 1:08:11.792
- Okay.

1:08:11.876 --> 1:08:13.209
- Okay, rehearsing.

1:08:13.292 --> 1:08:15.000
- Look at this, Jenna.

1:08:15.083 --> 1:08:16.959
As you can plainly see,

1:08:17.042 --> 1:08:19.375
my right boob is much higher
than my left boob,

1:08:19.459 --> 1:08:22.167
and Dawn here has pasty,
pasty skin.

1:08:22.250 --> 1:08:25.042
I'm stuck in a marriage
to drooling Phil, the invalid,

1:08:25.125 --> 1:08:26.918
and Dawn eats TV dinners alone,

1:08:27.000 --> 1:08:29.667
but still we wouldn't
rather be you.

1:08:29.751 --> 1:08:32.417
- I do have pasty, pasty skin.

1:08:32.500 --> 1:08:34.459
- It was so funny

1:08:34.542 --> 1:08:37.959
and some, like,
real female feelings.

1:08:38.042 --> 1:08:40.709
- I know what you're thinking,
'cause you called him an elf.

1:08:40.792 --> 1:08:42.584
- Only 'cause you initially
called him an elf.

1:08:42.667 --> 1:08:43.834
- You're jealous.
- No.

1:08:43.918 --> 1:08:46.167
- You are.
Because you have

1:08:46.250 --> 1:08:48.417
the most controlling husband
in the world.

1:08:48.500 --> 1:08:51.334
And you are stuck there,
but I have found someone

1:08:51.417 --> 1:08:52.792
who loves me to death.

1:08:52.876 --> 1:08:54.042
- Well,
let's hope not to death.

1:08:54.125 --> 1:08:56.417
- And I am happy!
- Good.

1:08:56.500 --> 1:08:58.876
- She understood

1:08:58.959 --> 1:09:01.042
when you weren't being honest
in a scene.

1:09:01.125 --> 1:09:04.167
I had built this "are you
happy enough?" Cal speech,

1:09:04.250 --> 1:09:06.209
and she goes, "Well, we got
it, and it's great.

1:09:06.292 --> 1:09:08.000
I'm so happy, are you happy?"
I go, "Yeah, I mean"--

1:09:08.083 --> 1:09:09.542
She goes, "Great.

1:09:09.626 --> 1:09:12.000
"Hey, can we try one where

1:09:12.083 --> 1:09:14.542
no one's ever
asked you this before?"

1:09:14.626 --> 1:09:18.334
- I mean, would you call
yourself a happy man?

1:09:18.417 --> 1:09:19.709
- Well, if you're
asking me a serious question,

1:09:19.792 --> 1:09:21.876
I'll tell you.

1:09:21.959 --> 1:09:24.000
I'm happy enough.

1:09:24.083 --> 1:09:25.542
I don't expect much.

1:09:25.626 --> 1:09:27.000
I don't give much.

1:09:27.083 --> 1:09:28.792
I don't get much.

1:09:28.876 --> 1:09:31.209
I generally enjoy
whatever comes up.

1:09:33.167 --> 1:09:34.751
That's my truth,

1:09:34.834 --> 1:09:37.751
summed up
for your feminine judgment.

1:09:37.834 --> 1:09:40.083
I'm happy enough.

1:09:40.167 --> 1:09:42.417
- I felt safe, because I knew

1:09:42.500 --> 1:09:44.918
that if she didn't get
what she wanted,

1:09:45.000 --> 1:09:46.709
she wouldn't stop, you know?

1:09:46.792 --> 1:09:48.083
That's really what it--
as an actor,

1:09:48.167 --> 1:09:50.918
you just wanna feel like--
like she knows what she wants,

1:09:51.000 --> 1:09:53.042
she knows when she gets it,
and--

1:09:53.125 --> 1:09:55.459
you know, and that she has--
and she knows when I'm--

1:09:55.542 --> 1:09:57.542
I'm not doing it.

1:09:57.626 --> 1:09:58.667
[glass shatters]

1:09:58.751 --> 1:10:01.125
[all gasping, murmuring]

1:10:02.334 --> 1:10:04.417
Jenna,

1:10:04.500 --> 1:10:06.375
I'm very upset with you.

1:10:12.792 --> 1:10:14.167
- Well, of course, you remember
none of this, right?

1:10:14.250 --> 1:10:16.584
- Mm-mm. Just from the movie.
- Uh-huh.

1:10:17.876 --> 1:10:19.083
Brings back a lot
of memories.

1:10:21.751 --> 1:10:24.083
- Bye.
- Bye.

1:10:24.167 --> 1:10:26.292
- We--we went to the road,

1:10:26.375 --> 1:10:28.959
like, um, that we walked in
at the end of the movie.

1:10:29.042 --> 1:10:30.667
- No way!
- Yeah.

1:10:30.751 --> 1:10:34.292
Bye-bye-bye.
[squealing]

1:10:34.375 --> 1:10:36.292
- [chuckles]
Bye.

1:10:36.375 --> 1:10:37.417
I mean, you were too little.
- Yeah.

1:10:37.500 --> 1:10:38.918
- You probably
don't even remember that.

1:10:39.000 --> 1:10:40.834
I remember that.
- She doesn't remember.

1:10:40.918 --> 1:10:43.292
- You wouldn't let your mom
out of your sight.

1:10:43.375 --> 1:10:47.250
And, um, so we just had--
she had to run and hide

1:10:47.334 --> 1:10:49.709
behind a bush,
and I was just holding you

1:10:49.792 --> 1:10:51.792
until you kind of calmed down,

1:10:51.876 --> 1:10:54.042
and then we sort of sang
together.

1:10:55.375 --> 1:10:59.334
Baby, don't cry,
gonna make a pie

1:10:59.417 --> 1:11:04.792
Hold you forever
in the middle of my heart

1:11:10.626 --> 1:11:14.959
- On the Monday
when we learned of the arrest,

1:11:15.042 --> 1:11:17.876
that's when we also learned
that "Waitress" had

1:11:17.959 --> 1:11:20.459
been accepted into Sundance.

1:11:20.542 --> 1:11:23.459
- I'm sure as she was waiting
for Sundance's response,

1:11:23.542 --> 1:11:25.459
she was uncertain
whether or not--

1:11:25.542 --> 1:11:26.626
- Yeah, she had no idea.

1:11:26.709 --> 1:11:28.626
And I remember once saying
to her, like,

1:11:28.709 --> 1:11:32.000
"Do you know
what you have here?"

1:11:32.083 --> 1:11:35.626
And she said, "If it gets into
Sundance and people see it,

1:11:35.709 --> 1:11:36.834
it could be big."

1:11:36.918 --> 1:11:39.375
- I didn't think
about the film.

1:11:39.459 --> 1:11:41.334
After what happened
with Adrienne,

1:11:41.417 --> 1:11:43.209
I didn't think about the film.

1:11:43.292 --> 1:11:46.042
I just--
it seemed insignificant.

1:11:46.125 --> 1:11:48.209
And then, um--

1:11:48.292 --> 1:11:49.792
and then we went to Sundance.

1:11:49.876 --> 1:11:53.584
[soft rock music]

1:11:53.667 --> 1:11:56.000
- Sundance was something
I dreaded going to.

1:11:57.959 --> 1:12:02.083
I knew going in, it was gonna
be one of the hardest things

1:12:02.167 --> 1:12:05.042
that any of us
in the family had to do.

1:12:06.751 --> 1:12:08.667
- You looked ashen.

1:12:09.667 --> 1:12:11.751
You were there,
you were present,

1:12:11.834 --> 1:12:15.667
but it was everything--
every ounce of energy,

1:12:15.751 --> 1:12:19.125
you know, just to be standing
up and functioning right.

1:12:20.334 --> 1:12:23.918
- It's the most heart-wrenching

1:12:24.000 --> 1:12:27.751
and most beautiful thing
that I've ever experienced.

1:12:27.834 --> 1:12:30.083
We were all there, and--
and you were there,

1:12:30.167 --> 1:12:31.459
and your family was there.

1:12:31.542 --> 1:12:35.083
And we watched this movie,
all of us, for the first time.

1:12:38.334 --> 1:12:41.167
[dramatic music playing]

1:12:41.250 --> 1:12:42.375
- Oh.

1:12:43.792 --> 1:12:45.709
Look what you did.

1:12:45.792 --> 1:12:47.709
You made me almost pretty.

1:12:47.792 --> 1:12:50.375
- What do you mean
"almost" pretty?

1:12:50.459 --> 1:12:51.542
You're lovely.

1:12:51.626 --> 1:12:53.834
- Lot of people say how,
obviously, at Sundance,

1:12:53.918 --> 1:12:55.667
you know, just seeing her--

1:12:55.751 --> 1:12:57.959
I know how it was for me,
but seeing her--

1:12:58.042 --> 1:13:00.083
- It was a killer!
Are you kidding?

1:13:00.167 --> 1:13:02.209
- Aw, I'm sorry, hon.

1:13:02.292 --> 1:13:03.459
- I looked,
and then I didn't look.

1:13:03.542 --> 1:13:06.167
I remember I was crying so,

1:13:06.250 --> 1:13:08.083
and there was a man--
I don't know who--

1:13:08.167 --> 1:13:09.918
who he belonged to, whatever,

1:13:10.000 --> 1:13:12.751
and I remember he--
he was, like, trying to--

1:13:12.834 --> 1:13:14.959
"It's okay, it's okay,
don't worry."

1:13:15.042 --> 1:13:17.959
- As soon as the opening
credits started rolling,

1:13:18.042 --> 1:13:19.500
Elaine just buried her head
in my shoulder

1:13:19.584 --> 1:13:20.959
and started
bawling her eyes out.

1:13:21.042 --> 1:13:23.584
"That's my baby, that's
my baby, that's my baby."

1:13:23.667 --> 1:13:25.667
- We were all just confused

1:13:25.751 --> 1:13:28.626
by how that could be a part
of this world,

1:13:28.709 --> 1:13:31.751
that this murder could
be anywhere connected

1:13:31.834 --> 1:13:37.417
to this movie
that was so much about life.

1:13:37.500 --> 1:13:40.042
- Oh, my God.
Here it is.

1:13:40.125 --> 1:13:43.959
A character and script
and story and everything

1:13:44.042 --> 1:13:46.125
that I know so well.

1:13:46.209 --> 1:13:50.125
It just seemed simultaneously

1:13:50.209 --> 1:13:52.584
magical and unfair.

1:13:53.918 --> 1:13:56.459
- Everywhere we went,
people gave you

1:13:56.542 --> 1:14:00.542
such effusive compliments
about being in "Waitress."

1:14:00.626 --> 1:14:02.667
I mean,
I got into every suite,

1:14:02.751 --> 1:14:04.000
I got into every party--

1:14:04.083 --> 1:14:05.500
"Oh, you're in 'Waitress,'
aren't you?"

1:14:05.584 --> 1:14:07.292
I mean, it was the darling.

1:14:07.375 --> 1:14:12.876
- Here was the success
of this film

1:14:12.959 --> 1:14:16.125
by a woman who struggled
as a filmmaker

1:14:16.209 --> 1:14:17.834
to get to this point.

1:14:17.918 --> 1:14:19.626
This was gonna be her moment.

1:14:19.709 --> 1:14:21.626
How are we here

1:14:21.709 --> 1:14:23.334
and she's not?

1:14:23.417 --> 1:14:26.417
[soft music]

1:14:28.125 --> 1:14:32.876
I wanted her there,
so I took a little vial

1:14:32.959 --> 1:14:35.375
of her ashes.

1:14:35.459 --> 1:14:37.709
And I got up really early
that day

1:14:37.792 --> 1:14:40.083
and went to the top
of the hill,

1:14:40.167 --> 1:14:43.042
stood in the middle
of the street,

1:14:43.125 --> 1:14:46.042
and just, like,
walked the yellow line

1:14:46.125 --> 1:14:48.042
and just...

1:14:48.125 --> 1:14:49.709
threw her ashes in the air.

1:14:49.792 --> 1:14:53.000
- No, you never told me that.
- All the way down the street.

1:14:53.083 --> 1:14:57.375
And then that night, I brought
the little vial again,

1:14:57.459 --> 1:15:00.000
and because I wanted her
in the theater.

1:15:00.083 --> 1:15:02.000
This was her moment.

1:15:05.125 --> 1:15:06.834
It was her--
her premiere.

1:15:06.918 --> 1:15:08.542
She had to be there.

1:15:11.459 --> 1:15:15.584
And I remember
throwing ashes in--in the air,

1:15:15.667 --> 1:15:17.584
and Harvey Weinstein walked
right by.

1:15:17.667 --> 1:15:19.375
And they landed on his--
- Whoa.

1:15:19.459 --> 1:15:21.209
- On his shoulders.

1:15:21.292 --> 1:15:26.292
And I just, like,
started laughing on the inside,

1:15:26.375 --> 1:15:29.709
because I just--
like, literally it was as if

1:15:29.792 --> 1:15:32.709
Adrienne was right next to me

1:15:32.792 --> 1:15:37.542
laughing and thinking that was
the funniest thing ever.

1:15:41.083 --> 1:15:44.667
- I started out saying,
"I'm never ever going to speak

1:15:44.751 --> 1:15:46.876
"like it's harder
because I'm a woman.

1:15:47.000 --> 1:15:50.167
That's the last thing I'm ever,
ever gonna do."

1:15:50.250 --> 1:15:53.959
And then, you know,
five years later, I was saying,

1:15:54.042 --> 1:15:56.167
"You know, it really is much
harder because I'm a woman,

1:15:56.250 --> 1:15:58.292
"much harder,
and I want everyone to know.

1:15:58.375 --> 1:16:00.459
And I want to talk about it
constantly."

1:16:00.542 --> 1:16:04.584
And--and then,
now I'm sort of back to feeling

1:16:04.667 --> 1:16:06.334
like it's hard for everybody.

1:16:06.417 --> 1:16:08.584
It's hard.
It's a hard business.

1:16:14.334 --> 1:16:16.417
- I just
made a decision early on

1:16:16.500 --> 1:16:21.918
that I not only need
to accept what happened,

1:16:22.000 --> 1:16:25.876
in that "shit happens,
life's not fair" kind of way,

1:16:25.959 --> 1:16:28.918
but also try
to spin some gold from it,

1:16:29.000 --> 1:16:32.876
to turn what is probably
the most horrifying negative

1:16:32.959 --> 1:16:34.959
I'll ever experience
in my life

1:16:35.042 --> 1:16:38.334
to something positive
somewhere, somehow.

1:16:38.417 --> 1:16:42.834
Um, so that's what
got me started very early on

1:16:42.918 --> 1:16:47.292
on creating a foundation
to support women filmmakers.

1:16:52.083 --> 1:16:55.000
[Sara Bareilles' "Opening Up"]

1:16:56.667 --> 1:17:01.626
- 2007, saw that film,
loved the characters,

1:17:01.709 --> 1:17:03.792
felt for them,
cared about them.

1:17:03.876 --> 1:17:06.959
The storytelling, of course,
a wonderful story.

1:17:07.042 --> 1:17:08.792
It felt like
those characters would reach

1:17:08.876 --> 1:17:11.209
an emotional moment
in their lives

1:17:11.292 --> 1:17:15.250
where they had to burst out
in song or dance.

1:17:15.334 --> 1:17:16.918
-  The day starts
like the rest we've seen

1:17:17.000 --> 1:17:19.918
Another carbon copy
of an old routine

1:17:20.000 --> 1:17:22.584
-  Days keep coming
-  One out, one in

1:17:22.667 --> 1:17:23.918
all:  They keep coming

1:17:24.000 --> 1:17:26.417
- Make that coffee
strong enough to chew.

1:17:27.959 --> 1:17:30.125
- I think in the year 2019,

1:17:30.209 --> 1:17:33.959
we'll be 1,300 performances
deep into our Broadway run.

1:17:34.042 --> 1:17:36.667
I mean, that's preposterous.

1:17:36.751 --> 1:17:40.125
- It was always
really precious to us

1:17:40.209 --> 1:17:43.792
to maintain the integrity of--
of her mission statement

1:17:43.876 --> 1:17:47.500
and the sort of bold
feminism of it.

1:17:47.584 --> 1:17:52.125
- It's delivered
with such humor and fantasy

1:17:52.209 --> 1:17:56.125
with Jenna's pies,
and it's just

1:17:56.209 --> 1:17:59.250
got its own signature tone.

1:17:59.334 --> 1:18:02.417
- There's victory--
there's human victory here

1:18:02.500 --> 1:18:04.250
in--of the best kind.

1:18:04.334 --> 1:18:06.250
-  Sugar

1:18:09.792 --> 1:18:14.083
Sugar, butter,
flour

1:18:17.334 --> 1:18:19.417
- I did a lot
of talking to Adrienne.

1:18:19.500 --> 1:18:22.709
I--like, out loud,
at the piano,

1:18:22.792 --> 1:18:25.709
come on in, come play,
come play with me.

1:18:25.792 --> 1:18:27.334
Let's create something.

1:18:27.417 --> 1:18:30.209
-  She is messy

1:18:30.292 --> 1:18:33.375
But she's kind

1:18:33.459 --> 1:18:37.125
She is lonely

1:18:37.209 --> 1:18:39.584
Most of the time

1:18:39.667 --> 1:18:44.292
She is all of this
mixed up and baked

1:18:44.375 --> 1:18:48.334
In a beautiful pie

1:18:48.417 --> 1:18:52.334
She is gone,
but she used to be

1:18:52.417 --> 1:18:56.375
Mine

1:18:56.459 --> 1:19:00.792
- Jenna's someone who is
endlessly loyal and caretaking

1:19:00.876 --> 1:19:03.334
and self-diminishing.

1:19:03.417 --> 1:19:04.417
- The queen of kindness.

1:19:04.500 --> 1:19:06.083
- The queen of kindness
and goodness

1:19:06.167 --> 1:19:07.459
to--to a fault.

1:19:07.542 --> 1:19:10.751
It's then so powerful
to watch that person,

1:19:10.834 --> 1:19:13.918
which we can all relate to
in some way, shape, or form,

1:19:14.000 --> 1:19:16.042
rise above that limitation.

1:19:16.125 --> 1:19:18.834
And to watch it be a happy
ending, it's so nice.

1:19:18.918 --> 1:19:21.500
-  But used to be

1:19:21.584 --> 1:19:28.542
Mine

1:19:30.709 --> 1:19:33.375
Oh, used to be

1:19:33.459 --> 1:19:40.375
Mine

1:19:45.375 --> 1:19:50.918
We just had this goal
of honoring her.

1:19:51.000 --> 1:19:53.626
And whenever things would
get tough--

1:19:53.709 --> 1:19:57.459
I remember at one point,
I had a sticky up on my mirror

1:19:57.542 --> 1:20:00.334
in Broadway that said,
"It's for Adrienne."

1:20:00.417 --> 1:20:07.083
Mixed up and baked
in a beautiful pie

1:20:09.000 --> 1:20:12.042
She is gone

1:20:12.125 --> 1:20:15.334
But she used to be

1:20:15.417 --> 1:20:20.834
Mine

1:20:20.918 --> 1:20:23.167
[applause]

1:20:23.250 --> 1:20:26.959
- I want to take a moment
to talk about the fifth, uh,

1:20:27.042 --> 1:20:29.918
female on the team,
and that's Adrienne Shelly.

1:20:30.000 --> 1:20:32.959
[cheers and applause]

1:20:36.751 --> 1:20:39.375
For those of who don't know,
but I think most of you do,

1:20:39.459 --> 1:20:43.125
Adrienne wrote, directed,
and was one of the stars

1:20:43.209 --> 1:20:46.417
of the movie "Waitress,"
and she died

1:20:46.500 --> 1:20:49.083
before the movie was bought
at Sundance,

1:20:49.167 --> 1:20:52.876
before she could experience
how embraced

1:20:52.959 --> 1:20:55.250
her beautiful gem
that she created was--

1:20:55.334 --> 1:20:57.459
this beautiful pie she created.

1:20:57.542 --> 1:21:00.751
And she wrote this movie
before the Me Too movement,

1:21:00.834 --> 1:21:03.542
when stories
about quiet bravery of women

1:21:03.626 --> 1:21:05.209
were deemed unimportant.

1:21:05.292 --> 1:21:08.250
And they were impossible to get
made, and she got it made.

1:21:08.334 --> 1:21:11.417
To Adrienne, I think I speak
for all of us when I say,

1:21:11.500 --> 1:21:13.375
as we all look up,

1:21:13.459 --> 1:21:15.751
thank you for taking us
to the moon, moon pie.

1:21:15.834 --> 1:21:18.834
[cheers and applause]

1:21:23.042 --> 1:21:27.792
- I was sobbing the whole time
watching the show.

1:21:27.876 --> 1:21:30.959
And towards the end,
I felt paralyzed.

1:21:31.042 --> 1:21:33.459
Like, I didn't want
to leave the theater.

1:21:33.542 --> 1:21:35.417
I couldn't leave.

1:21:35.500 --> 1:21:38.125
Uh, and eventually,
I made my way out,

1:21:38.209 --> 1:21:40.667
and again, I was,
like, hanging around.

1:21:40.751 --> 1:21:42.876
I didn't know for what.
Like, I just didn't want

1:21:42.959 --> 1:21:45.209
to leave the theater.
It was such--

1:21:45.292 --> 1:21:48.209
I don't know,
this was like my connection

1:21:48.292 --> 1:21:52.125
with Adrienne, this is,
you know, my last kind of...

1:21:54.042 --> 1:21:55.751
Time with her.

1:21:58.167 --> 1:22:00.626
- The thing that I picked up
from working with Hal,

1:22:00.709 --> 1:22:05.709
he gave me a--you know, a sort
of way to drop my own timidity,

1:22:05.792 --> 1:22:09.667
you know, to--to understand
how important it is to--

1:22:09.751 --> 1:22:12.125
if--when you're--
when you're making a film,

1:22:12.209 --> 1:22:15.709
that you should ask for what
it is you want, you know,

1:22:15.792 --> 1:22:19.000
and to not sort of shy away
from what your own,

1:22:19.083 --> 1:22:20.667
uh, ideas are.

1:22:20.751 --> 1:22:23.500
His films are unique and they
could only be made by him.

1:22:23.584 --> 1:22:26.250
And I'm hoping that one day,

1:22:26.334 --> 1:22:29.167
someone might say that
about me too.

1:22:31.209 --> 1:22:34.167
[suspenseful music]

1:22:45.375 --> 1:22:47.250
- Did you ever meet Pillco?

1:22:47.334 --> 1:22:49.209
- I saw him in court a couple
of times.

1:22:49.292 --> 1:22:51.375
- Can I see him?
Show me a picture of him.

1:22:51.459 --> 1:22:53.542
- Yeah,
if that's what you want.

1:22:53.626 --> 1:22:55.918
- Will you ever meet him?
- Yes, someday.

1:22:56.000 --> 1:22:57.083
Not to forgive him

1:22:57.167 --> 1:22:58.918
but to learn the truth
about what he did

1:22:59.000 --> 1:23:01.125
and make him know
how special Mommy was.

1:23:01.209 --> 1:23:02.709
- I'd never forgive him.

1:23:02.792 --> 1:23:04.042
And when you show me
his picture,

1:23:04.125 --> 1:23:07.250
we should draw a mustache, elf
ears, and devil horns on it.

1:23:09.584 --> 1:23:11.500
[phone rings]

1:23:11.584 --> 1:23:13.667
- Here's Sophie.

1:23:13.751 --> 1:23:15.584
Hey, Shmoph.
- Hi.

1:23:15.667 --> 1:23:17.334
How are you feeling
about today?

1:23:17.417 --> 1:23:20.334
- I'm a little nervous
but not as nervous

1:23:20.417 --> 1:23:22.876
as I think I'll probably feel
when I see the prison.

1:23:22.959 --> 1:23:24.667
- Yeah.
Text me if you want.

1:23:24.751 --> 1:23:27.125
- Okay.
I love you so much.

1:23:27.209 --> 1:23:28.209
- Okay,
I love you too so much.

1:23:28.292 --> 1:23:29.250
Good luck.

1:23:30.626 --> 1:23:35.209
- Now, I'm not coming here
'cause I need to beat him up.

1:23:35.292 --> 1:23:37.626
Just want him to be honest.

1:23:37.709 --> 1:23:41.250
You know, I want him
to shed light on stuff,

1:23:41.334 --> 1:23:46.125
and I want him
to acknowledge what he did

1:23:46.209 --> 1:23:50.250
and who he took
and the consequence of that.

1:23:53.542 --> 1:23:55.709
It'd be funny if everything I
said just goes out the window

1:23:55.792 --> 1:23:58.375
and I fly
into some fucking rage.

1:23:58.459 --> 1:24:00.417
Have to be carted out of there

1:24:00.500 --> 1:24:02.083
and that's the end
of the interview.

1:24:04.292 --> 1:24:07.292
[tense music]

1:24:14.209 --> 1:24:16.417
I think I wanna vomit.

1:24:47.667 --> 1:24:50.209
13 years ago, Adrienne died.

1:24:54.918 --> 1:24:57.584
Part of me died that day.

1:24:58.834 --> 1:25:00.834
There's some things I--I--
I need to know,

1:25:00.918 --> 1:25:03.209
some things I'd like to know.

1:25:03.292 --> 1:25:06.083
There's also some things
I'd like you to know.

1:25:06.167 --> 1:25:08.083
That's really
why I'm here today.

1:25:10.250 --> 1:25:11.751
I'm not here to attack you.

1:25:11.834 --> 1:25:13.626
I'm just here to share

1:25:13.709 --> 1:25:17.334
what I've had in my head
for 13 years.

1:25:18.125 --> 1:25:20.417
I'm sure you've had a lot
to think about too.

1:25:21.667 --> 1:25:23.459
- I'm sorry.

1:25:25.542 --> 1:25:28.792
I wish I could go back
and change things.

1:25:28.876 --> 1:25:30.459
I can't.

1:25:31.751 --> 1:25:34.375
[speaking Spanish]

1:25:34.459 --> 1:25:37.167
- I was never aggressive.

1:25:37.250 --> 1:25:38.959
I never hurt anyone.

1:25:40.667 --> 1:25:46.876
- I need to understand
how someone like you,

1:25:46.959 --> 1:25:49.876
who says he never hurt anyone--

1:25:49.959 --> 1:25:51.083
help me understand how you--

1:25:51.167 --> 1:25:53.500
how you turned into a murderer
that day.

1:25:53.584 --> 1:25:56.584
- [speaking Spanish]

1:25:58.584 --> 1:26:02.667
- I came to this country
owing $13,500.

1:26:07.584 --> 1:26:11.209
My mom put my--
put her house in the bank

1:26:11.292 --> 1:26:12.876
so that I could have money.

1:26:18.709 --> 1:26:22.083
I was looking to find
how am I gonna send the money.

1:26:25.000 --> 1:26:27.375
I started working
in apartments.

1:26:35.167 --> 1:26:38.000
And one day, I saw someone
come out of the apartments.

1:26:41.667 --> 1:26:44.667
And I said to myself, "I'm
gonna go in to look for money."

1:26:44.751 --> 1:26:48.751
- So you were looking

1:26:48.834 --> 1:26:52.959
to rob apartments that day?

1:26:53.042 --> 1:26:56.083
- [speaking Spanish]

1:26:57.417 --> 1:26:59.083
- I had been doing it
for a while,

1:26:59.167 --> 1:27:01.626
since I started needing money.

1:27:03.792 --> 1:27:05.918
Nothing ever happened--
- In that building or anywhere?

1:27:06.000 --> 1:27:09.292
- [speaking Spanish]
- Everywhere.

1:27:09.375 --> 1:27:11.918
Wherever they put me to work.

1:27:15.542 --> 1:27:18.792
That day, they sent me
to work where she lived--

1:27:18.876 --> 1:27:20.834
where your wife lived.

1:27:24.000 --> 1:27:28.000
So when I put my ear
to the door, the door opened.

1:27:33.167 --> 1:27:34.709
I was afraid
that I was gonna get caught,

1:27:34.792 --> 1:27:36.167
but then I saw a bag.

1:27:39.918 --> 1:27:42.459
When I took out the money,
I put the bag back in.

1:27:47.250 --> 1:27:51.375
And that's when the lady
came out and she ran after me.

1:27:55.375 --> 1:27:57.042
And when she started yelling
at me...

1:28:00.334 --> 1:28:03.876
The only word that I heard
that she said was "police."

1:28:09.209 --> 1:28:10.584
She went to grab the phone.

1:28:14.584 --> 1:28:16.417
I got behind her
and covered her mouth

1:28:16.500 --> 1:28:18.334
and told her not
to call the police.

1:28:21.292 --> 1:28:24.334
I lost my mind.
I lost it.

1:28:27.417 --> 1:28:29.375
And I was choking her
with my hand.

1:28:32.584 --> 1:28:34.751
At the same time,
I was covering her mouth...

1:28:36.459 --> 1:28:38.000
So that she wouldn't
make noise.

1:28:40.876 --> 1:28:43.042
I took my hand off,

1:28:43.125 --> 1:28:44.500
and I let her go.

1:28:45.918 --> 1:28:47.417
And I saw her--

1:28:48.918 --> 1:28:50.417
That her--

1:28:50.500 --> 1:28:52.334
her lips were blue.

1:28:54.417 --> 1:28:56.417
Then I thought,
"Oh, I killed her."

1:28:59.417 --> 1:29:01.584
And I took her to the bathroom.

1:29:05.209 --> 1:29:08.167
And then I hung her
like if she committed suicide.

1:29:08.250 --> 1:29:10.542
- Did you think you got--
you got away with it?

1:29:10.626 --> 1:29:13.334
- [speaking Spanish]
- Yes.

1:29:14.834 --> 1:29:17.125
- I want to show you
some pictures.

1:29:19.500 --> 1:29:21.042
You took a wife.

1:29:23.209 --> 1:29:25.834
You took someone
who I was madly in love with.

1:29:27.792 --> 1:29:30.167
You took a mother.

1:29:30.250 --> 1:29:32.918
That's my daughter
with her mom.

1:29:33.000 --> 1:29:35.417
They don't have anything
anymore.

1:29:37.000 --> 1:29:39.042
And they had everything.

1:29:42.000 --> 1:29:46.125
That was taken October 31st.

1:29:46.209 --> 1:29:48.250
That was the day
before you killed her.

1:29:52.542 --> 1:29:54.459
Adrienne missed a lot.

1:29:54.542 --> 1:29:56.459
She missed birthdays.

1:29:56.542 --> 1:30:00.459
That's the first birthday
after her mom left her.

1:30:00.542 --> 1:30:03.542
This is a recent birthday,
still no mom.

1:30:05.500 --> 1:30:07.959
This is what she was
left with--me.

1:30:08.042 --> 1:30:10.375
Just me.

1:30:11.667 --> 1:30:15.083
First day she rode a bike.
Her mom wasn't there for that.

1:30:15.167 --> 1:30:17.751
First days of school.

1:30:17.834 --> 1:30:20.083
Mommy wasn't there for that.

1:30:20.167 --> 1:30:22.834
She's a damn good
soccer player.

1:30:22.918 --> 1:30:26.167
Mommy's never seen
any of her games.

1:30:26.250 --> 1:30:29.626
This is--
this is the life you took away.

1:30:38.209 --> 1:30:41.125
[somber music]

1:30:46.584 --> 1:30:48.209
Okay.
I'm done.

1:30:50.417 --> 1:30:54.459
- [speaking Spanish]
- I'm sorry.

1:30:54.542 --> 1:30:56.125
- Stand up.

1:31:20.125 --> 1:31:21.667
[door slams]

1:31:28.292 --> 1:31:30.500
- I remember being very young,

1:31:30.584 --> 1:31:34.083
and I just wanted
to know exactly what happened.

1:31:36.250 --> 1:31:38.417
- What did Mommy look like
when you found her?

1:31:38.500 --> 1:31:40.209
- She looked bad.

1:31:40.292 --> 1:31:42.667
- Where was she?
- In the bathroom.

1:31:42.751 --> 1:31:44.334
- How did he kill her?
- He strangled her

1:31:44.417 --> 1:31:45.500
and put a rope
around her neck

1:31:45.584 --> 1:31:47.417
so it'd look
like she killed herself.

1:31:47.500 --> 1:31:49.918
But no one believed that.
She loved you so much

1:31:50.000 --> 1:31:51.250
and would never
have left you.

1:31:51.334 --> 1:31:53.792
- I bet it was scary.
- It was.

1:31:53.876 --> 1:31:55.959
- What did you tell me
when she died?

1:31:56.042 --> 1:31:57.292
- I told you
her body stopped working

1:31:57.375 --> 1:31:58.626
and she wasn't coming home.

1:31:58.709 --> 1:32:00.083
- Did I know
what dying meant?

1:32:00.167 --> 1:32:02.417
- No.
- That was good, right?

1:32:02.500 --> 1:32:04.834
- Yeah.
You were so little.

1:32:08.459 --> 1:32:11.542
- How often do I think
about him in my life?

1:32:11.626 --> 1:32:13.000
Every day.

1:32:13.083 --> 1:32:16.083
Whenever I think of her,
I think of him.

1:32:16.167 --> 1:32:19.709
But it's also different,
because I'm grieving her

1:32:19.792 --> 1:32:21.334
in a different way

1:32:21.417 --> 1:32:23.459
and more so kind of.

1:32:24.834 --> 1:32:27.709
both: One, two, three.

1:32:27.792 --> 1:32:31.125
- She's entering an age where,
you know,

1:32:31.209 --> 1:32:34.626
nobody can take the place
of a mother,

1:32:34.709 --> 1:32:39.292
and I'm sure she...
wishes she were here

1:32:39.375 --> 1:32:43.834
and needs her
for so many different things.

1:32:43.918 --> 1:32:47.125
- If you could bring Mommy
back for one day tomorrow,

1:32:47.209 --> 1:32:49.292
what would you get up and do?

1:32:50.500 --> 1:32:52.250
- Um...

1:32:53.500 --> 1:32:54.792
Just walk around.

1:32:54.876 --> 1:32:56.042
- Mm-hmm.

1:32:57.125 --> 1:32:59.083
Would you guys talk a lot?
- Yeah.

1:32:59.167 --> 1:33:00.918
- What would you tell her?

1:33:12.584 --> 1:33:15.834
- I don't know.
Just whatever came to mind.

1:33:15.918 --> 1:33:18.459
'Cause I could, you know?
- Mm-hmm.

1:33:20.918 --> 1:33:25.167
I struggle with the concept
of closure.

1:33:25.250 --> 1:33:29.042
My life will always
be about grief.

1:33:29.125 --> 1:33:31.292
You know?
There will always be

1:33:31.375 --> 1:33:33.042
that ghost in the room.

1:33:33.125 --> 1:33:36.959
The love that I had at that
time, it didn't go anywhere.

1:33:37.042 --> 1:33:43.167
It just, like, froze.
Like, she is frozen in time.

1:33:43.250 --> 1:33:45.626
- Every morning, we talk.

1:33:45.709 --> 1:33:47.459
She helps me.

1:33:47.542 --> 1:33:48.792
I loved her.

1:33:48.876 --> 1:33:51.083
I loved her.

1:33:52.125 --> 1:33:55.667
I can't even
believe it sometimes.

1:33:55.751 --> 1:33:57.375
She's so alive.

1:33:57.459 --> 1:34:00.000
She was so alive, Andy.
She was so alive.

1:34:00.083 --> 1:34:02.000
- I think about her every day.

1:34:02.083 --> 1:34:04.709
I think about my girls' pain
in not knowing their aunt,

1:34:04.792 --> 1:34:06.876
Sophie's pain.

1:34:06.959 --> 1:34:11.792
- To me, her greatest joy
was that child.

1:34:14.042 --> 1:34:16.209
- She's a little wind-up toy.

1:34:16.292 --> 1:34:21.042
- So to watch Sophie grow
into this incredible woman

1:34:21.125 --> 1:34:25.083
is terribly painful.

1:34:25.167 --> 1:34:27.334
And beautiful, because she's
such an amazing kid

1:34:27.417 --> 1:34:29.167
and has so much
of Adrienne in her

1:34:29.250 --> 1:34:32.000
and all the mannerisms
and all the sweetness

1:34:32.083 --> 1:34:33.375
and the silliness

1:34:33.459 --> 1:34:35.792
and sense of humor
and all of that,

1:34:35.876 --> 1:34:38.709
but Adrienne not getting
to have that...

1:34:38.792 --> 1:34:40.250
- Mm-hmm.

1:34:40.334 --> 1:34:42.125
- Is worse than anything to me.

1:34:44.542 --> 1:34:47.125
- She was getting more
and more confident in her life

1:34:47.209 --> 1:34:49.959
as a mom, a wife,
and all that,

1:34:50.042 --> 1:34:52.834
but in her--
her creative life too,

1:34:52.918 --> 1:34:56.751
she had a very clear idea
where she wanted to go.

1:34:57.751 --> 1:35:00.042
- She craved
making great work.

1:35:00.125 --> 1:35:02.751
She craved
having her voice heard

1:35:02.834 --> 1:35:05.042
and her vision be out there.

1:35:05.792 --> 1:35:08.542
- You just--
with certain people, you know

1:35:08.626 --> 1:35:11.250
certain things are gonna happen
if they continue on.

1:35:12.584 --> 1:35:13.542
- Do you hear that?

1:35:13.626 --> 1:35:16.125
- With Adrienne,
it's always gonna be

1:35:16.209 --> 1:35:18.834
the what could've been,
what was.

1:35:24.209 --> 1:35:29.334
- I just have a very specific
kind of satisfaction

1:35:29.417 --> 1:35:32.500
when I walk around midtown
and see "Waitress"

1:35:32.584 --> 1:35:35.292
on a Broadway marquee.

1:35:35.375 --> 1:35:38.417
The majority of people that
are going to see that show

1:35:38.500 --> 1:35:42.125
every day come from all
different walks of life.

1:35:42.209 --> 1:35:44.167
They don't know her story.
They don't even know

1:35:44.250 --> 1:35:46.667
what the deal is
behind "Waitress."

1:35:46.751 --> 1:35:48.792
And judging it completely
on its own merits...

1:35:48.876 --> 1:35:50.542
- Well, sure.
- And having an incredible

1:35:50.626 --> 1:35:53.626
experience as an artist,

1:35:53.709 --> 1:35:57.000
that's the best
we can hope for.

1:35:57.083 --> 1:36:02.375
In that regard, what an
incredible thing she's done.

1:36:04.125 --> 1:36:08.792
- Creative desire.
Create life and celebrate life

1:36:08.876 --> 1:36:11.000
and contribute to the world.

1:36:11.083 --> 1:36:13.876
It's part of,
you know, being a woman.

1:36:13.959 --> 1:36:17.042
It's part of being
a human being, I think.

1:36:19.250 --> 1:36:20.417
- After we do
this interview,

1:36:20.500 --> 1:36:22.042
I'm just gonna give you
this tape, you know?

1:36:22.125 --> 1:36:26.125
And you can have it and, uh,
maybe, like, one day perhaps

1:36:26.209 --> 1:36:29.125
there's an off-chance that
your children might see it.

1:36:29.209 --> 1:36:32.167
- Mm, mm, mm!
Delicious baby.

1:36:32.250 --> 1:36:35.083
- What would you, if anything,
want them to know

1:36:35.167 --> 1:36:39.334
or understand about you
at this point in your life?

1:36:40.918 --> 1:36:43.375
- That I--you know, I--
I don't have them yet,

1:36:43.459 --> 1:36:48.042
but I...
I'm thinking of them.

1:36:48.125 --> 1:36:49.209
You know?

1:36:49.292 --> 1:36:53.459
I really want them
to have a good life.

1:37:00.042 --> 1:37:04.751
Yeah, their mother starred
in some movies and...

1:37:04.834 --> 1:37:08.167
was on magazine covers and...

1:37:08.250 --> 1:37:11.792
was admired by a few people,

1:37:11.876 --> 1:37:13.959
but, uh,

1:37:14.042 --> 1:37:18.918
none of that she considers
as important as they will be.

1:37:20.459 --> 1:37:22.250
- All right.
- All right, say bye-bye.

1:37:22.334 --> 1:37:24.083
- Bye-bye.
- Bye-bye.

1:37:24.167 --> 1:37:26.459
- All right, bye, camera.
- Say bye-bye.

1:37:26.542 --> 1:37:27.959
- Sophie, can you wave?

1:37:28.042 --> 1:37:29.375
Can you wave bye-bye
to the camera?

1:37:29.459 --> 1:37:32.083
- Wave bye-bye.
- Bye-bye.

1:37:41.834 --> 1:37:44.709
[expressive piano music]

1:39:35.959 --> 1:39:38.459
[bright tone]
